<EFX_PROPERTIES>
<A NAME="FIS_PROPERTIES"></A>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<B>
<!-- COMMAND=ADD_TXTHEX,"PMS287" -->
</B>
</FONT>
<FONT COLOR="#0C2E82" SIZE=2>
<B>
	Item&nbsp;2.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Properties
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	A description of the location and general character of our principal physical properties is included in Item&nbsp;1. "Business" and is incorporated herein
	by&nbsp;reference.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	We
	believe that our pipeline systems hold all rights, titles and interests in their respective pipeline systems. With respect to real property, our pipeline systems own or
	lease sites for compressor stations, meter stations, pipeline field offices and microwave towers. Our pipeline systems are constructed and operated on land owned by third parties, governmental
	authorities and others pursuant to leases, easements, rights-of-way, permits and licenses. We believe that our pipeline systems' properties are adequate and suitable for the conduct of their business
	in the&nbsp;future.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<I>
	Northern Border&nbsp;&#150;&nbsp;
</I>
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
	Approximately 90&nbsp;miles of Northern Border's pipeline system is
	located within the boundaries of the Fort Peck Indian Reservation in Montana. Northern Border has a pipeline right-of-way lease with the Assiniboine and Sioux Tribes of the Fort Peck Indian
	Reservation, the term of which expires in 2061. In conjunction with obtaining right-of-way access across tribal lands located within the exterior boundaries of the Fort Peck Indian Reservation,
	Northern Border also obtained right-of-way access across allotted lands located within the reservation boundaries. With the exception of one tract subject to a right-of-way grant expiring in 2035, the
	allotted lands are subject to a perpetual easement granted by the Bureau of Indian Affairs (BIA) for and on behalf of the individual allottees.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<I>
	Great Lakes
</I>
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&#150;&nbsp;Approximately 74&nbsp;miles of Great Lakes' pipeline system is located
	within the boundaries of three Indian reservations: the Leech Lake Chippewa Indian Reservation and the Fond du Lac Chippewa Indian Reservation in Minnesota, and the Bad River Chippewa Indian
	Reservation in Wisconsin. Great Lakes has right-of-way access, granted by the BIA, across allotted lands located within each reservation's boundaries that expire in 2018. Also, the Great Lakes
	pipeline crosses approximately 1,000&nbsp;feet in two tracts under perpetual easement, located within the Chippewa Indian Reservation in Lower&nbsp;Michigan.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	Please
	read Part&nbsp;I, Item&nbsp;1. "Business&nbsp;&#150;&nbsp;Narrative Description of
	Business&nbsp;&#150;&nbsp;Government Regulation&nbsp;&#150;&nbsp;Other" for more information regarding legislation affecting easements on
	tribal&nbsp;land.
</FONT>
</P>
<P ALIGN="RIGHT" STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<B>
<!-- COMMAND=ADD_TXTHEX,"PMS287" -->
</B>
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
	2015 ANNUAL
	REPORT&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
<!-- COMMAND=ADD_TXTHEX,"PMS287" -->

<EFX_LEGAL_PROCEEDINGS>
<A NAME="FIS_LEGAL_PROCEEDINGS"></A>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<B>
<!-- COMMAND=ADD_TXTHEX,"PMS287" -->
</B>
</FONT>
<FONT COLOR="#0C2E82" SIZE=2>
<B>
	Item&nbsp;3.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Legal Proceedings
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	We are involved in various legal proceedings that arise in the ordinary course of business, as well as proceedings that we consider material under federal securities
	regulations. Information regarding our pipeline systems' rate proceedings described in Item&nbsp;1. "Business&nbsp;&#150;&nbsp;Government
	Regulation&nbsp;&#150;&nbsp;Regulatory and Rate Proceedings" is incorporated herein by reference. We are also a party to the following legal proceedings:
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<I>
	Employees Retirement System of the City of St.&nbsp;Louis v. TC&nbsp;PipeLines&nbsp;GP,&nbsp;Inc., et&nbsp;al
</I>
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
	. On
	October&nbsp;13, 2015, an alleged unitholder of the Partnership filed a class action and derivative complaint in the Delaware Court of Chancery against the General Partner, TransCanada American
	Investments,&nbsp;Ltd. (TAIL) and TransCanada, and the Partnership as a nominal defendant. The complaint alleges direct and derivative claims for breach of contract, breach of the duty of good faith
	and fair dealing, aiding and abetting breach of contract, and tortious interference in connection with the 2015 GTN Acquisition, including the issuance by the Partnership of $95&nbsp;million in
	Class&nbsp;B Units and amendments to the Partnership Agreement to provide for the issuance of the Class&nbsp;B Units. Plaintiff seeks, among other things, to enjoin future issuances of
	Class&nbsp;B Units to TransCanada or any of its subsidiaries, disgorgement of certain distributions to the General Partner, TransCanada and any related entities, return of some or all of the
	Class&nbsp;B Units to the Partnership, rescission of the amendments to the Partnership Agreement, monetary damages and attorney fees. The Partnership has moved to dismiss the complaint and intends
	to defend vigorously against the claims asserted.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<I>
	Great Lakes v. Essar Steel Minnesota&nbsp;LLC, et&nbsp;al.
</I>
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&#150;&nbsp;On October&nbsp;29,
	2009, Great Lakes filed suit in the U.S.&nbsp;District Court, District of Minnesota, against Essar Minnesota&nbsp;LLC and certain Essar affiliates (collectively, Essar) for breach of its monthly
	payment obligation under its transportation services agreement with Great Lakes. Great Lakes sought to recover approximately $33&nbsp;million for past and future payments due under the agreement. On
	September&nbsp;16, 2015, following a jury trial, the federal district court judge entered a judgment in the amount of $32.9&nbsp;million in favor of Great Lakes. On September&nbsp;20, 2015,
	Essar appealed the decision to the United&nbsp;States Court of Appeals for the 8
<SUP>
	th
</SUP>
	&nbsp;Circuit (8
<SUP>
	th
</SUP>
	&nbsp;Circuit) based on an allegation of improper jurisdiction and
	a number of other rulings by the federal district judge. Essar was required to post a performance bond for the full value of the judgment pending appeal. The matter is expected to be heard by the
	8
<SUP>
	th
</SUP>
	&nbsp;circuit in&nbsp;2016.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<I>
	Northern Border Pipeline Company v. State of South Dakota Department of Revenue
</I>
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&#150;&nbsp;On
	February&nbsp;28, 2011, the South Dakota Department of Revenue (Department of Revenue)
	assessed a use tax in the amount of approximately $6&nbsp;million on Northern Border for shipper supplied natural gas used to fuel compressors on Northern Border's pipeline system from
	July&nbsp;1, 2007 to December&nbsp;31, 2010. Following an unsuccessful rehearing, Northern Border received a favorable ruling on appeal by the South Dakota Circuit Court, Sixth Judicial Circuit,
	which decision was appealed by the Department of Revenue to the South Dakota Supreme Court. On August&nbsp;5, 2015, the South Dakota Supreme Court issued its decision in favor of Northern Border,
	ruling that the Department of Revenue could not assess use tax on gas burned in compressors on Northern Border's pipeline located in South Dakota because Northern Border did not own the gas. The
	decision resulted in Northern Border's reversal of $15&nbsp;million recorded liability, including interest and the related deferred asset on its books with no impact to the Partnership's earnings.
</FONT>
</P>
</EFX_LEGAL_PROCEEDINGS>

<EFX_MARKET>

<FONT COLOR="#0C2E82" SIZE=2>
<B>
	Item&nbsp;5.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Market for Registrant's Common Equity, Related Stockholder Matters and
	Issuer Purchases of Equity Securities
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	As of February&nbsp;26, 2016, there were 42&nbsp;registered holders of common units and approximately 12,200&nbsp;beneficial owners of common units, including common
	units held in street name. Our common units trade on the NYSE under the symbol&nbsp;"TCP."
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	As
	of February&nbsp;26, 2016, the Partnership had 64,317,449&nbsp;common units outstanding, of which 47,232,618&nbsp;were held by non-affiliates and
	17,084,831&nbsp;common units were held by subsidiaries of TransCanada, including 5,797,106&nbsp;common units held by our General Partner. Additionally, TransCanada, thorough our General Partner,
	owns 100&nbsp;percent of our IDRs and an effective two percent general partner interest in the Partnership. TransCanada also holds 100&nbsp;percent of our 1,900,000&nbsp;outstanding
	Class&nbsp;B units. There is no established public trading market for our IDRs and Class&nbsp;B&nbsp;units.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	The
	following table sets forth, for the periods indicated, the high and low sale prices per common unit, as reported by the NYSE, and the amount of cash distributions
	declared per common unit with respect to the corresponding periods. Cash distributions are paid within 45&nbsp;days after the end of each quarter to unitholders of record as of the
	record&nbsp;date.
</FONT>

<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	On February&nbsp;12, 2016, we paid a cash distribution of $59&nbsp;million to common unitholders and the General Partner,
	representing a cash distribution of $0.89 per common unit for the quarter ended December&nbsp;31, 2015. The distribution was allocated in the following manner: $57&nbsp;million to the common
	unitholders as of the close of business on February&nbsp;2, 2016 (including approximately $15&nbsp;million to TransCanada as holder of 17,084,831&nbsp;common units), and $2&nbsp;million to the
	General Partner in respect of its effective two percent general partner interest, which includes $1&nbsp;million of incentive distributions. In 2015, the Partnership made cash distributions to
	common unitholders and the General Partner that amounted to $228&nbsp;million compared to $212&nbsp;million in&nbsp;2014.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<I>
	Cash Distribution Policy
</I>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	Pursuant to the Partnership Agreement, the General Partner receives two percent of all cash distributions in regard to its general partner interest and is also entitled to
	incentive distributions as described below. The unitholders receive the remaining portion of the cash distribution. Our quarterly cash distributions to the unitholders comprise all of our Available
	Cash. Available Cash is defined in the Partnership Agreement and generally means, with respect to any quarter, all cash on hand at the end of a quarter less the amount of cash reserves that are
	necessary or appropriate, in the reasonable discretion of the General Partner,&nbsp;to:
</FONT>
</P>
<DL COMPACT>
<DT STYLE='FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;MARGIN-BOTTOM:-11PT;'>
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&#149;
</FONT>
</DT>
<DD STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	provide
	for the proper conduct of our business (including reserves for future capital expenditures and anticipated credit&nbsp;needs);
</FONT>
</DD>
</DL>
<P ALIGN="RIGHT" STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<B>
<!-- COMMAND=ADD_TXTHEX,"PMS287" -->
</B>
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
	2015 ANNUAL
	REPORT&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
<!-- COMMAND=ADD_TXTHEX,"PMS287" -->
</FONT>
<FONT COLOR="#0C2E82" SIZE=1>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
<B>
<!-- COMMAND=ADD_TXTHEX,"PMS287" -->
</B>
</FONT>
<FONT COLOR="#0C2E82" SIZE=2>
<B>
	37
</B>
</FONT>
</P>

<!-- ZEQ.=1,SEQ=37,EFW="2227406",CP="TC PIPELINES, LP",DN="1",CHK=790692,FOLIO='37',FILE='DISK132:[15ZCW1.15ZCW77001]DK77001A.;37',USER='CMACGOW',CD='23-FEB-2016;16:48' -->
<A NAME="A2227406Z10-K_HTM_PAGE_DK77001_1_38">
</A>
<DL COMPACT>
<DT STYLE='FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;MARGIN-BOTTOM:-11PT;'>
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&#149;
</FONT>
</DT>
<DD STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	comply
	with applicable laws or any debt instrument or other agreement to which we are subject;&nbsp;and
<BR>
<BR>
</FONT>
</DD>
<DT STYLE='FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;MARGIN-BOTTOM:-11PT;'>
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&#149;
</FONT>
</DT>
<DD STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	provide
	funds for cash distributions to unitholders and the General Partner in respect of any one or more of the next four&nbsp;quarters.
</FONT>
</DD>
</DL>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<I>
	Incentive Distributions
</I>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	The incentive distribution provisions of the Partnership Agreement provide that the General Partner receives 15&nbsp;percent of quarterly amounts distributed in excess of
	$0.81 per common unit, and a maximum of 25&nbsp;percent of quarterly amounts distributed in excess of $0.88 per common unit, provided the balance has been first distributed to unitholders on a
	pro&nbsp;rata basis. The amounts that trigger incentive distributions at various levels are subject to adjustment in certain events, as described in the Partnership Agreement.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	The
	first quarter 2015 distribution of $0.84 per common unit exceeded the first target of the General Partner's IDRs by $0.03 per common unit, resulting in an increase in
	the distribution on the General Partner interest from 2&nbsp;percent to 15&nbsp;percent on the incremental distribution in excess of the first&nbsp;target.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	The
	second, third and fourth quarter 2015 distributions of $0.89 per common unit exceeded the first and second targets of the General Partner's IDRs by $0.07 and $0.01 per
	common unit, respectively, resulting in an increase in the distribution on the General Partner interest from 2&nbsp;percent to 15&nbsp;percent on the incremental distribution in excess of the
	first target and from 15&nbsp;percent to 25&nbsp;percent on the incremental distribution in excess of the second&nbsp;target.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	In
	2015, we paid incentive distributions to our General Partner of approximately $2&nbsp;million (2014&nbsp;&#150;&nbsp;$1&nbsp;million).
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<I>
	Distributions to Class&nbsp;B units
</I>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	On January&nbsp;21, 2016, the board of directors of our General Partner declared distributions to Class&nbsp;B unitholders in the amount of $12&nbsp;million which amount
	was paid on February&nbsp;12, 2016. The Class&nbsp;B distribution represents an amount based upon 30&nbsp;percent of GTN's distributable cash flow during the nine months ended
	December&nbsp;31, 2015 less $15&nbsp;million.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	See
	Part&nbsp;II, Item&nbsp;7. "Management's Discussion and Analysis of Financial Condition and Results of Operations&nbsp;&#150;&nbsp;Liquidity
	and Capital Resources" and Item&nbsp;13. "Certain Relationships and Related Transactions, and Director Independence" for additional information about cash distributions.
</FONT>
</P>

<EFX_MANAGEMENTS_DISCUSSION>
<A NAME="FIS_MANAGEMENTS_DISCUSSION"></A>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<B>
<!-- COMMAND=ADD_TXTHEX,"PMS287" -->
</B>
</FONT>
<FONT COLOR="#0C2E82" SIZE=2>
<B>
	Item&nbsp;7.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Management's Discussion and Analysis of Financial
	Condition and Results of&nbsp;Operations
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	Management's Discussion and Analysis is intended to give our unitholders an opportunity to view the Partnership through the eyes of our management. We have done so by providing
	management's current assessment of, and outlook of the business of the Partnership. Our discussion and analysis includes the&nbsp;following:
</FONT>
</P>
<DL COMPACT>
<DT STYLE='FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;MARGIN-BOTTOM:-11PT;'>
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&#149;
</FONT>
</DT>
<DD STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	EXECUTIVE
	OVERVIEW;
<BR>
<BR>
</FONT>
</DD>
<DT STYLE='FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;MARGIN-BOTTOM:-11PT;'>
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&#149;
</FONT>
</DT>
<DD STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	HOW
	WE EVALUATE OUR OPERATIONS;
<BR>
<BR>
</FONT>
</DD>
<DT STYLE='FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;MARGIN-BOTTOM:-11PT;'>
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&#149;
</FONT>
</DT>
<DD STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	RESULTS
	OF OPERATIONS;
<BR>
<BR>
</FONT>
</DD>
<DT STYLE='FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;MARGIN-BOTTOM:-11PT;'>
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&#149;
</FONT>
</DT>
<DD STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	LIQUIDITY
	AND CAPITAL RESOURCES;
<BR>
<BR>
</FONT>
</DD>
<DT STYLE='FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;MARGIN-BOTTOM:-11PT;'>
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&#149;
</FONT>
</DT>
<DD STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	CRITICAL
	ACCOUNTING ESTIMATES;
<BR>
<BR>
</FONT>
</DD>
<DT STYLE='FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;MARGIN-BOTTOM:-11PT;'>
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&#149;
</FONT>
</DT>
<DD STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	CONTINGENCIES;
	and
<BR>
<BR>
</FONT>
</DD>
<DT STYLE='FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;MARGIN-BOTTOM:-11PT;'>
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&#149;
</FONT>
</DT>
<DD STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	RELATED
	PARTY TRANSACTIONS.
</FONT>
</DD>
</DL>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	The
	following discussion and analysis should be read in conjunction with Part&nbsp;IV, Item&nbsp;15. "Exhibits and Financial Statements Schedules."
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<B>
<!-- COMMAND=ADD_TXTHEX,"PMS287" -->
</B>
</FONT>
<FONT COLOR="#0C2E82" SIZE=2>
<B>
	EXECUTIVE OVERVIEW
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	Net income (loss) attributable to controlling interests was $13&nbsp;million or $(0.03) per common unit in 2015 compared to $172&nbsp;million, or $2.67 per common unit in
	2014. Adjusted earnings were $212&nbsp;million or $3.03 per common unit in 2015, an increase of $40&nbsp;million, or $0.36 per common unit over 2014 adjusted earnings.
</FONT>
</P>
<P ALIGN="RIGHT" STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<B>
<!-- COMMAND=ADD_TXTHEX,"PMS287" -->
</B>
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
	2015 ANNUAL
	REPORT&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
<!-- COMMAND=ADD_TXTHEX,"PMS287" -->
</FONT>
<FONT COLOR="#0C2E82" SIZE=1>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
<B>
<!-- COMMAND=ADD_TXTHEX,"PMS287" -->
</B>
</FONT>
<FONT COLOR="#0C2E82" SIZE=2>
<B>
	39
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
<HR NOSHADE>
<P STYLE='FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE:ALWAYS'>
</P>
<!-- ZEQ.=3,SEQ=39,EFW="2227406",CP="TC PIPELINES, LP",DN="1",CHK=552166,FOLIO='39',FILE='DISK132:[15ZCW1.15ZCW77001]DK77001A.;37',USER='CMACGOW',CD='23-FEB-2016;16:48' -->
<A NAME="A2227406Z10-K_HTM_PAGE_DK77001_1_40">
</A>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	Cash
	distributions declared per common unit increased five percent from $3.33 per common unit in 2014 to $3.51 per common unit in&nbsp;2015.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	EBITDA
	increased by seven percent to $365&nbsp;million and Distributable cash flow increased by 14&nbsp;percent to $291&nbsp;million.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<I>
	PNGTS Acquisition
</I>
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&#150;&nbsp;On January&nbsp;1, 2016, we acquired a 49.9&nbsp;percent
	interest in PNGTS from TransCanada for $223&nbsp;million plus a preliminary purchase price adjustment of $3&nbsp;million. The purchase price consisted of $191&nbsp;million in cash (including the
	preliminary purchase price of $3&nbsp;million) and the assumption of approximately $35&nbsp;million in proportionate PNGTS debt. The Partnership funded the cash portion of the transaction using
	proceeds received from our ATM program and additional borrowings under our Senior Credit Facility. The purchase agreement provides for additional payments to TransCanada ranging from $5&nbsp;million
	up to a total of $50&nbsp;million if pipeline capacity is expanded to various thresholds during the fifteen year period following the date of&nbsp;closing.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	PNGTS
	is a high-capacity, high-pressure interstate natural gas pipeline which began serving New&nbsp;England's energy needs in March&nbsp;1999. The pipeline system is
	strategically located in the northeastern United&nbsp;States. The pipeline connects with the TQM Pipeline at the Canadian border and shares facilities with the Maritimes and Northeast Pipeline from
	Westbrook, Maine to a connection with the Tennessee Gas Pipeline System near Boston, Massachusetts.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	This
	transaction adds a new market geography for us, further diversifying our cash flow stream and extending our breadth of operations. Continuing changes in the
	New&nbsp;England and Canadian Maritime gas markets in which PNGTS operates are expected which should lead to future growth opportunities for this pipeline system.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<I>
	Investment in Great Lakes Impairment Charge
</I>
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&#150;&nbsp;Despite the recent improvement in income
	from our investment in Great Lakes since 2013, including favorable current year results, its long-term value has been adversely impacted by the changing natural gas flows in its market region as well
	as our conclusion in the fourth quarter that other strategic alternatives to increase its utilization or revenue were no longer feasible. As a result, we determined that the carrying value of our
	investment in Great Lakes was in excess of its fair value and the decline is not temporary. Accordingly, we concluded that the carrying value of our investment in Great Lakes was&nbsp;impaired.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	Our
	analysis determined that the fair value of our investment in Great Lakes is $465&nbsp;million, resulting in an impairment charge of $199&nbsp;million in the fourth
	quarter of 2015, reflected as Impairment of equity-method investment on our Statements of Income for the year ended December&nbsp;31,&nbsp;2015.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<B>
<!-- COMMAND=ADD_TXTHEX,"PMS287" -->
</B>
</FONT>
<FONT COLOR="#0C2E82" SIZE=2>
<B>
	Outlook of Our Business
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	TransCanada, the ultimate parent company of our General Partner, is currently executing a large capital program that includes $13&nbsp;billion Canadian of near-term growth
	opportunities that are expected to be complete by 2018. Over the medium to longer-term, TransCanada is also advancing $45&nbsp;billion Canadian of commercially secured large-scale projects, and
	various other initiatives backed by long-term contracts or cost-of-service business models. Depending on market conditions and actual funding needs, TransCanada views the dropdown of its remaining
	U.S.&nbsp;natural gas pipeline assets into the Partnership as an important financing option as it executes its capital growth program. There can be no assurance when and on what terms these assets
	will be offered to the Partnership.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	The
	Partnership's financial performance is expected to benefit from its recent acquisitions, including the acquisition of an interest in PNGTS from TransCanada. Despite
	uncertainty in energy commodity prices, our portfolio of seven FERC-regulated interstate natural gas pipelines is expected to deliver generally stable results in 2016 due to ship-or-pay contracts with
	creditworthy customers.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<B>
<!-- COMMAND=ADD_TXTHEX,"PMS287" -->
</B>
</FONT>
<FONT COLOR="#0C2E82" SIZE=2>
<B>
	40
</B>
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;TC
	PIPELINES, LP
</FONT>
</P>

<A NAME="A2227406Z10-K_HTM_PAGE_DK77001_1_41">
</A>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<B>
<!-- COMMAND=ADD_TXTHEX,"PMS287" -->
</B>
</FONT>
<FONT COLOR="#0C2E82" SIZE=2>
<B>
	HOW WE EVALUATE OUR OPERATIONS
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	We use certain non-GAAP financial measures that do not have any standardized meaning under GAAP because we believe they enhance the understanding of our operating performance.
	We use the following non-GAAP measures:
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<B>
<!-- COMMAND=ADD_TXTHEX,"PMS287" -->
</B>
</FONT>
<FONT COLOR="#0C2E82" SIZE=2>
<B>
	Adjusted earnings and Adjusted earnings per common unit
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	We have evaluated our financial performance and position inclusive of the impairment charge to our investment in Great Lakes recognized during the fourth quarter of 2015,
	however, we believe it is not reflective of our underlying
	operations during the periods presented. Therefore, these measures exclude the impact of the $199&nbsp;million non-cash impairment charge.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<B>
<!-- COMMAND=ADD_TXTHEX,"PMS287" -->
</B>
</FONT>
<FONT COLOR="#0C2E82" SIZE=2>
<B>
	EBITDA
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	We use EBITDA as a proxy of our operating cash flow and current operating profitability. It measures our earnings from our pipeline systems before certain expenses
	are&nbsp;deducted.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<B>
<!-- COMMAND=ADD_TXTHEX,"PMS287" -->
</B>
</FONT>
<FONT COLOR="#0C2E82" SIZE=2>
<B>
	Distributable Cash Flows
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	Total distributable cash flow and distributable cash flow provide measures of distributable cash generated during the current earnings period.
</FONT>
</P>
<EFX_RESULTS_OF_OPERATIONS>
<A NAME="FIS_RESULTS_OF_OPERATIONS"></A>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<B>
<!-- COMMAND=ADD_TXTHEX,"PMS287" -->
</B>
</FONT>
<FONT COLOR="#0C2E82" SIZE=2>
<B>
	RESULTS OF OPERATIONS
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	We believe that the following presentation of the earnings contribution from each of our pipeline systems will enhance investors' understanding of the way we analyze our
	financial performance. However, this presentation is not meant to be considered in isolation or as a substitute for results prepared in accordance with&nbsp;GAAP.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	Our
	equity interests in Northern Border and Great Lakes, and ownership of GTN, Bison, North Baja and Tuscarora were our only material sources of income in 2015. Therefore,
	our results of operations and cash flows were influenced by, and reflect the same factors that influenced, our pipeline systems. See Part&nbsp;1, Item&nbsp;1.&nbsp;"Business."
</FONT>
</P>

<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<I>
	Year Ended December&nbsp;31, 2015 Compared with the Year Ended December&nbsp;31, 2014
</I>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	Net income attributable to controlling interests decreased by $159&nbsp;million to $13&nbsp;million in 2015 compared to $172&nbsp;million in 2014, resulting in a net loss
	per common unit during the year of $0.03 after allocations to the General Partner and to the Class&nbsp;B units. This decrease was primarily the result of the recognition of a $199&nbsp;million
	non-cash impairment charge to our investment in Great Lakes (See&nbsp;Part&nbsp;II, Item&nbsp;7. "Management's Discussion and Analysis of Financial Condition and Results of
	Operations&nbsp;&#150;&nbsp;Critical Accounting Estimates&nbsp;&#150;&nbsp;Impairment of Equity Investments, Goodwill and Long-Lived
	Assets&nbsp;&#150;&nbsp;Equity Investments.")
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	Adjusted
	earnings increased by $40&nbsp;million, an increase of $0.36 per common unit. This increase was primarily due to the net effect&nbsp;of:
</FONT>
</P>
<DL COMPACT>
<DT STYLE='FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;MARGIN-BOTTOM:-11PT;'>
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&#149;
</FONT>
</DT>
<DD STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	higher
	net income from GTN mainly due to higher revenues from the sale of short-term services;
<BR>
<BR>
</FONT>
</DD>
<DT STYLE='FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;MARGIN-BOTTOM:-11PT;'>
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&#149;
</FONT>
</DT>
<DD STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	higher
	net income from Bison mainly due to lower expenses related to pipeline integrity program spending and lower property taxes as compared to&nbsp;2014;
<BR>
<BR>
</FONT>
</DD>
<DT STYLE='FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;MARGIN-BOTTOM:-11PT;'>
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&#149;
</FONT>
</DT>
<DD STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	lower
	equity earnings from Northern Border primarily due to lower revenues from the sale of short-term services as a result of the milder winter in 2015 compared
	to&nbsp;2014;
<BR>
<BR>
</FONT>
</DD>
<DT STYLE='FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;MARGIN-BOTTOM:-11PT;'>
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&#149;
</FONT>
</DT>
<DD STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	higher
	equity earnings from Great Lakes primarily due to additional revenues from new contracts with ANR, a related&nbsp;party;
<BR>
<BR>
</FONT>
</DD>
<DT STYLE='FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;MARGIN-BOTTOM:-11PT;'>
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&#149;
</FONT>
</DT>
<DD STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	the
	acquisitions of the remaining interests in GTN and Bison whereby the Partnership now owns 100&nbsp;percent of GTN and Bison effective April&nbsp;1, 2015 and
	October&nbsp;1, 2014, respectively;&nbsp;and
</FONT>
</DD>
</DL>

<EFX_LIQUIDITY_CAPITAL>
<A NAME="FIS_LIQUIDITY_CAPITAL"></A>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<B>
<!-- COMMAND=ADD_TXTHEX,"PMS287" -->
</B>
</FONT>
<FONT COLOR="#0C2E82" SIZE=2>
<B>
	LIQUIDITY AND CAPITAL RESOURCES
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<B>
<!-- COMMAND=ADD_TXTHEX,"PMS287" -->
</B>
</FONT>
<FONT COLOR="#0C2E82" SIZE=2>
<B>
	Overview
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	Our principal sources of liquidity include distributions received from our investments in partially owned affiliates, operating cash flows from our consolidated subsidiaries,
	public offerings of debt and equity, term loans and our bank
</FONT>
</P>
<P ALIGN="RIGHT" STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<B>
<!-- COMMAND=ADD_TXTHEX,"PMS287" -->
</B>
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
	2015 ANNUAL
	REPORT&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
<!-- COMMAND=ADD_TXTHEX,"PMS287" -->
</FONT>
<FONT COLOR="#0C2E82" SIZE=1>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
<B>
<!-- COMMAND=ADD_TXTHEX,"PMS287" -->
</B>
</FONT>
<FONT COLOR="#0C2E82" SIZE=2>
<B>
	43
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
<HR NOSHADE>
<P STYLE='FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE:ALWAYS'>
</P>
<!-- ZEQ.=7,SEQ=43,EFW="2227406",CP="TC PIPELINES, LP",DN="1",CHK=833601,FOLIO='43',FILE='DISK132:[15ZCW1.15ZCW77001]DK77001A.;37',USER='CMACGOW',CD='23-FEB-2016;16:48' -->
<A NAME="A2227406Z10-K_HTM_PAGE_DK77001_1_44">
</A>
<BR>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	credit
	facility. The Partnership funds its operating expenses, debt service and cash distributions primarily with operating cash flows. Long-term capital needs may be met through the issuance of
	long-term debt and/or&nbsp;equity.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	Our
	pipeline systems' principal sources of liquidity are cash generated from operating activities, long-term debt offerings, bank credit facilities and equity contributions
	from their owners. Our pipeline systems have historically funded operating expenses, debt service and cash distributions to their owners primarily with operating cash flow. However, since the fourth
	quarter of 2010, Great Lakes has funded its debt repayments with cash calls to its owners. Northern Border also funded $62&nbsp;million of debt repayment in 2013 with a cash call to
	its&nbsp;owners.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	Capital
	expenditures are funded by a variety of sources, including cash generated from operating activities, borrowings under bank credit facilities, issuance of senior
	unsecured notes or equity contributions from our pipeline systems' owners. The ability of our pipeline systems to access the debt capital markets under reasonable terms depends on their financial
	position and general market conditions.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	The
	Partnership's pipeline systems monitor the creditworthiness of their customers and have credit provisions included in their tariffs which, although limited by FERC,
	allow them to request credit support as circumstances dictate.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	Our
	cash flow is based on the distributions from our portfolio of seven pipelines. Overall, we believe that our pipeline systems' ability to obtain financing at reasonable
	rates, together with a history of consistent cash flow from operating activities, provide a solid foundation to meet future liquidity and capital requirements. Over the next 12&nbsp;months, we
	expect to be able to fund our liquidity requirements, including our distributions, at the Partnership level, utilizing our cash flow and our existing Senior Credit Facility if&nbsp;required.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<B>
<!-- COMMAND=ADD_TXTHEX,"PMS287" -->
</B>
</FONT>
<FONT COLOR="#0C2E82" SIZE=2>
<B>
	Issuance of Class&nbsp;B Units to TransCanada
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	The Class&nbsp;B units issued on April&nbsp;1, 2015 represent limited partner interests in us and entitle TransCanada to an annual distribution which is an amount based on
	30&nbsp;percent of GTN's annual distributions after achieving certain annual thresholds.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	During
	the current year, we allocated a certain portion of our income to the Class&nbsp;B units representing the excess of 30&nbsp;percent of GTN's distribution over the
	2015 threshold level of $15&nbsp;million. The allocated amount of $12&nbsp;million was paid by the Partnership on February&nbsp;12, 2016. See also Note&nbsp;9 within Part&nbsp;IV,
	Item&nbsp;15. "Exhibits and Financial Statements Schedules."
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	For
	2016, the threshold level is $20&nbsp;million and we expect such threshold will be exceeded in the third quarter of 2016. Our cash flows will continue to be impacted
	by distributions payable to the Class&nbsp;B&nbsp;units.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	Please
	read Notes&nbsp;6 and&nbsp;7 within Part&nbsp;IV, Item&nbsp;15. "Exhibits and Financial Statements Schedules" for more detailed disclosures on the 2015 GTN
	Acquisition and Issuance of Class&nbsp;B&nbsp;units.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<B>
<!-- COMMAND=ADD_TXTHEX,"PMS287" -->
</B>
</FONT>
<FONT COLOR="#0C2E82" SIZE=2>
<B>
	EBITDA and&nbsp;Distributable Cash Flow
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	EBITDA is an approximate measure of our operating cash flow during the current earnings period and reconciles directly to the net income amount presented. It measures our
	earnings before deducting interest, depreciation and amortization and net income attributable to non-controlling interests, and it includes earnings from our equity investments.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	Total
	distributable cash flow and distributable cash flow provide measures of distributable cash generated during the current earnings period and reconcile directly to the
	net income amount presented.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	Total
	distributable cash flow includes EBITDA
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
<I>
	plus:
</I>
</FONT>
</P>
<DL COMPACT>
<DT STYLE='FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;MARGIN-BOTTOM:-11PT;'>
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&#149;
</FONT>
</DT>
<DD STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	Distributions
	from our equity investments
</FONT>
</DD>
</DL>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<B>
<!-- COMMAND=ADD_TXTHEX,"PMS287" -->
</B>
</FONT>
<FONT COLOR="#0C2E82" SIZE=2>
<B>
	44
</B>

<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;TC
	PIPELINES, LP
</FONT>
</P>

	from our equity investments,

<FONT SIZE=2>

<BR>

</FONT>

<DT STYLE='FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;MARGIN-BOTTOM:-11PT;'>
<FONT SIZE=2>

</FONT>
</DT>
<DD STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT SIZE=2>

	to non-controlling interests, and
<BR>
<BR>
</FONT>
</DD>
<DT STYLE='FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;MARGIN-BOTTOM:-11PT;'>
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&#149;
</FONT>
</DT>
<DD STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	Maintenance
	capital expenditures
</FONT>
</DD>
</DL>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	Distributable
	cash flow is computed net of distributions declared to the General Partner and distributions allocable to Class&nbsp;B units. Distributions declared to the
	General Partner are based on its effective two percent interest plus an amount equal to incentive distributions. Distributions allocable to the Class&nbsp;B units equal 30&nbsp;percent of GTN's
	distributable cash flow for the nine months ended December&nbsp;31, 2015 less $15&nbsp;million.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	Distributable
	cash flow information and EBITDA are presented to assist investors in evaluating our business performance. We believe these measures provide additional
	meaningful information in evaluating our financial performance and cash distribution capability. As well, management uses these measures as a basis for recommendations to our General Partner's board
	of directors regarding the distribution amount to be declared each&nbsp;quarter.
</FONT>
</P>

	results prepared in accordance with GAAP. Additionally, these measures as presented may not be comparable to similarly titled measures of other companies.

	Part&nbsp;IV, Item&nbsp;15. "Exhibits and Financial Statements Schedules" for information.
<BR>
<BR>
</FONT>
</DD>

	presented here represent depreciation of Plant, property and equipment and Amortization of debt issuance costs. Please read Note&nbsp;11 within
	Part&nbsp;IV, Item&nbsp;15. "Exhibits and Financial Statements Schedules" for information.
<BR>
<BR>
</FONT>
</DD>
<DT STYLE='FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;MARGIN-BOTTOM:-9PT;'>

	(d)

</DT>
<DD STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">

	here are calculated in accordance with the cash distribution policies of these entities. Distributions from each of our equity investments
	represent our respective share of these entities' quarterly distributable cash during the current reporting period.
<BR>
<BR>
</FONT>
</DD>
<DT STYLE='FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;MARGIN-BOTTOM:-9PT;'>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">

	(e)
</FONT>
</FONT>
</DT>
<DD STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
	Amounts
	here are calculated in accordance with the cash distribution policies of our consolidated subsidiaries. Distributions to non-controlling interests
	represent the respective share of quarterly distributable cash during the current reporting period not owned by&nbsp;us.
<BR>
<BR>
</FONT>
</DD>
<DT STYLE='FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;MARGIN-BOTTOM:-9PT;'>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:6PT;POSITION:RELATIVE;TOP:-2PT;ADD_SUP:2PT;">
	(f)
</FONT>
</FONT>
</DT>
<DD STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
	"Total
	Distributable Cash Flow" and "Distributable Cash Flow" represent the amount of distributable cash generated by the Partnership subsidiaries and
	equity investments during the current earnings period and thus reconcile directly to the net income amount presented.
</FONT>
</DD>

<A NAME="A2227406Z10-K_HTM_PAGE_DK77001_1_47">
</A>
<UL>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
	The
	calculation differs from the previous non-GAAP measures "Partnership Cash Flows before General Partner distributions" and "Partnership Cash Flows" as the previously used measures primarily
	reflected cash received during the period through distributions from our subsidiaries and equity investments that were generated from the prior quarter's financial results. The amounts reflected here
	have been adjusted to reflect the calculation as described above and to present the comparable "Total Distributable Cash flow" and "Distributable Cash Flow" from the previous periods.
</FONT>
</P>
</UL>

	declared to the General Partner for the year ended December&nbsp;31, 2015 included an incentive distribution of approximately
	$3&nbsp;million (2014&nbsp;&#150;&nbsp;$1&nbsp;million).

<BR>
</FONT>
</DD>

<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
	During
	the nine months ended December&nbsp;31, 2015, 30&nbsp;percent of GTN's total distributions was $27&nbsp;million; therefore the distributions
	allocable to the Class&nbsp;B units is $12&nbsp;million, representing the amount that exceeded the threshold level of $15&nbsp;million. The Class&nbsp;B distribution is determined and payable
	annually.
<BR>
</FONT>
<BR>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
	On
	January&nbsp;21, 2016, the board of directors of our General Partner declared distributions to Class&nbsp;B unitholders in the amount of $12&nbsp;million which was paid on February&nbsp;12,
	2016. Please read Notes&nbsp;6, 9 and&nbsp;12 within Part&nbsp;IV, Item&nbsp;15. "Exhibits and Financial Statements Schedules" and Part&nbsp;II, Item&nbsp;7. "Management Discussion and
	Analysis of Financial Condition and Results of Operations&nbsp;&#150;&nbsp;Liquidity and Capital Resources&nbsp;&#150;&nbsp;Issuance of Class&nbsp;B
	Units to TransCanada."

</P>

<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">

<I>
	Year Ended December&nbsp;31, 2015 Compared with the Year Ended December&nbsp;31, 2014
</I>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	EBITDA increased by $24&nbsp;million compared to the same period in 2014. The increase was primarily due to the net effect&nbsp;of:
</FONT>
</P>
<DL COMPACT>
<DT STYLE='FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;MARGIN-BOTTOM:-11PT;'>
<FONT SIZE=2>

<FONT SIZE=2>
	higher
	GTN revenue from the sale of short-term services;
<BR>
<BR>
</FONT>
</DD>
<DT STYLE='FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;MARGIN-BOTTOM:-11PT;'>
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&#149;
</FONT>
</DT>
<DD STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	higher
	equity earnings from Great Lakes, mainly due to revenues related to contracts with affiliates;
<BR>
<BR>
</FONT>
</DD>
<DT STYLE='FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;MARGIN-BOTTOM:-11PT;'>
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&#149;
</FONT>
</DT>
<DD STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	lower
	equity earnings from Northern Border, mainly due to lower revenues from the sale of short-term services as a result of the milder winter in 2015 compared to
	2014;&nbsp;and
<BR>
<BR>
</FONT>
</DD>
<DT STYLE='FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;MARGIN-BOTTOM:-11PT;'>
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&#149;
</FONT>
</DT>
<DD STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	lower
	expenses in the current period mainly due to lower spending on pipeline integrity work and lower property&nbsp;taxes.
</FONT>
</DD>
</DL>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	Distributable
	cash flow increased by $35&nbsp;million in the twelve months ended December&nbsp;31, 2015 compared to the same period in 2014 primarily due to the net
	effect&nbsp;of:

<!-- ZEQ.=11,SEQ=47,EFW="2227406",CP="TC PIPELINES, LP",DN="1",CHK=117422,FOLIO='47',FILE='DISK132:[15ZCW1.15ZCW77001]DK77001A.;37',USER='CMACGOW',CD='23-FEB-2016;16:48' -->
<A NAME="A2227406Z10-K_HTM_PAGE_DK77001_1_48">
</A>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<I>
	Other Cash Flows
</I>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	On January&nbsp;1, 2016, the Partnership acquired a 49.9&nbsp;percent interest in PNGTS from a subsidiary of TransCanada. The total purchase price of the PNGTS Acquisition
	was $223&nbsp;million plus preliminary purchase price adjustments of 3&nbsp;million. The purchase price consisted of $191&nbsp;million in cash (including the preliminary purchase price
	adjustment of $3&nbsp;million) and the assumption of $35&nbsp;million in proportional PNGTS debt. The Partnership funded the cash portion of the transaction using proceeds received from our ATM
	program and additional borrowings in our Senior Credit Facility. Refer to Note&nbsp;22 within Part&nbsp;IV, Item&nbsp;15. "Exhibits and Financial Statement Schedules" for additional disclosure
	regarding the PNGTS Acquisition.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	In
	March and October of 2015, 2014 and 2013, the Partnership made equity contributions totaling $9&nbsp;million in each year to Great Lakes to fund debt repayments.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	On
	April&nbsp;1, 2015, the Partnership acquired the remaining 30&nbsp;percent interest in GTN from a subsidiary of TransCanada. The total purchase price of the 2015 GTN
	Acquisition was $446&nbsp;million plus the final purchase price adjustment of $11&nbsp;million, for a total of $457&nbsp;million. The purchase price consisted of $264&nbsp;million in cash
	(including the final purchase price adjustment of $11&nbsp;million), the assumption of $98&nbsp;million in proportional GTN debt and the issuance of 1,900,000&nbsp;new Class&nbsp;B units to
	TransCanada valued at $50 each, representing a limited partner interest in the Partnership with a total value of $95&nbsp;million. Refer to Note&nbsp;6 within Part&nbsp;IV, Item&nbsp;15.
	"Exhibits and Financial Statement Schedules" for additional disclosure regarding the 2015 GTN Acquisition.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	On
	October&nbsp;1, 2014, the Partnership acquired the remaining 30&nbsp;percent interest in Bison from a subsidiary of TransCanada. The total purchase price of the 2014
	Bison Acquisition was $215&nbsp;million plus purchase price adjustments of approximately $2&nbsp;million. The acquisition of Bison was financed through a combination of (i)&nbsp;net proceeds
	from the ATM Program, and (ii)&nbsp;short-term financing. Refer to Note&nbsp;6 within Part&nbsp;IV, Item&nbsp;15. "Exhibits and Financial Statement Schedules" for additional disclosure
	regarding the 2014 Bison Acquisition.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	In
	the second quarter of 2014, the Partnership made a payment of $25&nbsp;million in accordance with the 2013 Acquisition related to the attainment of certain events with
	respect to the Carty Lateral project.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	In
	November&nbsp;2013, the Partnership made an equity contribution totaling $31&nbsp;million to Northern Border to fund the repayment of a portion of the Northern Border
	Credit Facility.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	On
	July&nbsp;1, 2013, the Partnership acquired a 45&nbsp;percent membership interest in each of GTN and Bison from subsidiaries of TransCanada, increasing the
	Partnership's ownership in each of GTN and Bison to 70&nbsp;percent. The Partnership paid $921&nbsp;million in respect of this acquisition in 2013. It was financed with net proceeds from an equity
	issuance of $373&nbsp;million, borrowing of $500&nbsp;million in term loans, an $8&nbsp;million capital contribution from the General Partner, a draw under the Senior Credit Facility and cash on
	hand. Refer to Note&nbsp;6 within Part&nbsp;IV, Item&nbsp;15. "Exhibits and Financial Statement Schedules" for additional disclosure regarding the 2013 Acquisition.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	In
	the second quarter of 2013, Bison's former parent made an equity contribution to Bison of $18&nbsp;million which was used to repay inter-affiliate debt primarily
	related to pipeline construction costs, including reclamation and restoration&nbsp;work.
</FONT>
</P>

	633
</FONT>

<DL COMPACT>
<DT STYLE='FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;MARGIN-BOTTOM:-9PT;'>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:6PT;POSITION:RELATIVE;TOP:-2PT;ADD_SUP:2PT;">
	(a)
</FONT>
</FONT>
</DT>
<DD STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
	Interest
	payments on floating-rate debt are estimated using interest rates effective as of December&nbsp;31,&nbsp;2015.
</FONT>
</DD>
</DL>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	The Partnership's Senior Credit Facility consists of a $500&nbsp;million senior revolving credit facility with a banking syndicate,
	maturing November&nbsp;20, 2017, under which $200&nbsp;million was outstanding at December&nbsp;31, 2015 (2014&nbsp;&#150;&nbsp;$330&nbsp;million).
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	At
	the Partnership's option, the interest rate on the outstanding borrowings under the Senior Credit Facility may be lenders' base rate or LIBOR plus, in either case, an
	applicable margin that is based on the Partnership's long-term unsecured credit ratings. The Senior Credit Facility permits the Partnership to specify the portion of the borrowings to be covered by
	specific interest rate options and, for LIBOR-based borrowings, to specify the interest rate period. The Partnership is required to pay a commitment fee based on its credit rating and on the unused
	principal amount of the commitments under the Senior Credit Facility. The Senior Credit Facility has a feature whereby at any time, so long as no event of default has occurred and is continuing, the
	Partnership may request an increase in the Senior Credit Facility of up to $250&nbsp;million, but no lender has an obligation to increase their respective share of the&nbsp;facility.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	The
	LIBOR-based interest rate on the Senior Credit Facility averaged 1.44&nbsp;percent for the year ended December&nbsp;31, 2015
	(2014&nbsp;&#150;&nbsp;1.41&nbsp;percent).
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	On
	July&nbsp;1, 2013, the Partnership entered into a term loan agreement with a syndicate of lenders for a $500&nbsp;million Term Loan Facility (2013 Term Loan
	Facility). On July&nbsp;2, 2013, the Partnership borrowed $500&nbsp;million under the 2013 Term Loan Facility, which matures on July&nbsp;1, 2018. The outstanding principal amount bears interest
	based, at the Partnership's election, on the LIBOR or the base rate plus, in either case, an applicable margin.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	The
	LIBOR based interest rate on the Term Loan Facility averaged 1.44&nbsp;percent for the year ended December&nbsp;31, 2015. After hedging activity, the interest rate
	incurred on the Term Loan Facility averaged 1.85&nbsp;percent for the year ended December&nbsp;31, 2015. Prior to hedging activities, the LIBOR-based interest rate was 1.50&nbsp;percent at
	December&nbsp;31, 2015 (2014-1.41&nbsp;percent).
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	On
	September&nbsp;30, 2015, the Partnership entered into an agreement for a $170&nbsp;million term loan credit facility (2015 Term Loan Facility). The Partnership
	borrowed $170&nbsp;million under the 2015 Term Loan Facility to refinance its
</FONT>
</P>
<P ALIGN="RIGHT" STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<B>
<!-- COMMAND=ADD_TXTHEX,"PMS287" -->
</B>
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
	2015 ANNUAL
	REPORT&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
<!-- COMMAND=ADD_TXTHEX,"PMS287" -->
</FONT>
<FONT COLOR="#0C2E82" SIZE=1>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
<B>
<!-- COMMAND=ADD_TXTHEX,"PMS287" -->
</B>
</FONT>
<FONT COLOR="#0C2E82" SIZE=2>
<B>
	49
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
<HR NOSHADE>
<P STYLE='FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE:ALWAYS'>
</P>
<!-- ZEQ.=13,SEQ=49,EFW="2227406",CP="TC PIPELINES, LP",DN="1",CHK=397789,FOLIO='49',FILE='DISK132:[15ZCW1.15ZCW77001]DK77001A.;37',USER='CMACGOW',CD='23-FEB-2016;16:48' -->
<A NAME="A2227406Z10-K_HTM_PAGE_DK77001_1_50">
</A>
<BR>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	Short-Term
	Loan Facility which matured on September&nbsp;30, 2015. The 2015 Term Loan Facility matures on October&nbsp;1, 2018. The LIBOR-based interest rate on the 2015 Term Loan Facility was
	1.39&nbsp;percent at December&nbsp;31,&nbsp;2015.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	The
	2013 Term Loan Facility and the 2015 Term Loan Facility (Term Loan Facilities) and the Senior Credit Facility require the Partnership to maintain a certain leverage
	ratio (debt to adjusted cash flow [net income plus cash distributions received, extraordinary losses, interest expense, expense for taxes paid or accrued, and depreciation and amortization
	expense less equity earnings and extraordinary gains]). In the quarter in which an acquisition has occurred, and the two quarters following the acquisition, the allowable leverage ratio
	increases to 5.50 to 1.00. Thereafter, the ratio returns to 5.00 to 1.00. The allowable ratio for the quarter ended December&nbsp;31, 2015 was 5.50 to 1.00. The leverage ratio was 4.68 to
	1.00&nbsp;as of December&nbsp;31, 2015. The Senior Credit Facility and the Term Loan Facilities contain additional covenants that include restrictions on entering into mergers, consolidations and
	sales of assets, granting liens, material amendments to the Partnership Agreement, incurrence of additional debt by the Partnership's subsidiaries and distributions to unitholders. Upon any breach of
	these covenants, amounts outstanding under the Senior Credit Facility and the Term Loan Facilities may become immediately due and&nbsp;payable.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	On
	March&nbsp;13, 2015, the Partnership closed a $350&nbsp;million public offering of senior unsecured notes bearing an interest rate of 4.375&nbsp;percent maturing
	March&nbsp;13, 2025. The net proceeds of $346&nbsp;million were used to fund a portion of the acquisition of the remaining 30&nbsp;percent interest in GTN (refer to Note&nbsp;6 within
	Part&nbsp;IV, Item&nbsp;15) and&nbsp;to reduce the amount outstanding under our Senior Credit Facility. The indenture for the notes contains customary investment grade covenants.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	On
	June&nbsp;1, 2015, GTN's 5.09&nbsp;percent unsecured Senior Notes matured. Also, on June&nbsp;1, 2015, GTN entered into a $75&nbsp;million unsecured variable rate
	term loan facility (Unsecured Term Loan Facility), which requires yearly principal payments until its maturity on June&nbsp;1, 2019. The variable interest is based on LIBOR plus an applicable
	margin. The LIBOR-based interest rate on the Unsecured Term Loan Facility for the year ended December&nbsp;31, 2015 averaged 1.16&nbsp;percent and was 1.15&nbsp;percent at December&nbsp;31,
	2015. GTN's Unsecured Senior Notes, along with this new Unsecured Term Loan Facility contain a covenant that limits total debt to no greater than 70&nbsp;percent of GTN's total capitalization. GTN's
	total debt to total capitalization ratio at December&nbsp;31, 2015 was 43.8&nbsp;percent.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	The
	Series&nbsp;D Senior Notes are secured by Tuscarora's transportation contracts, supporting agreements and substantially all of Tuscarora's property. The note purchase
	agreements contain certain provisions that include, among other items, limitations on additional indebtedness and distributions to&nbsp;partners.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	At
	December&nbsp;31, 2015, the Partnership was in compliance with its financial covenants.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	The
	fair value of the Partnership's long-term debt is estimated by discounting the future cash flows of each instrument at estimated current borrowing rates. The estimated
	fair value of the Partnership's long-term debt at December&nbsp;31, 2015 was $1,873&nbsp;million. As of February&nbsp;26, 2016, the Partnership had $365&nbsp;million outstanding under the
	Senior Credit Facility.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<I>
	Capital Requirements
</I>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	The Partnership is expected to make equity contributions totaling $9&nbsp;million to Great Lakes in 2016 for scheduled debt repayments.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	The
	Partnership's equity investee Northern Border has $100&nbsp;million of senior notes due in August&nbsp;2016. This amount will be refinanced with a combination of
	debt and/or equity at the discretion of the management committee. If an equity contribution is elected to repay the senior notes, the Partnership will be expected to make an equity contribution of up
	to $50&nbsp;million to Northern Border.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	In
	the fourth quarter of 2015, the Carty Lateral project went in service and the Partnership expects to spend approximately $3&nbsp;million to close out construction
	expenditures on this project in&nbsp;2016.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	We
	expect to be able to fund our capital requirements over the next 12&nbsp;months utilizing operating cash flow, equity issuances and when required, debt, including our
	existing Senior Credit Facility.
</FONT>
</P>

<DL COMPACT>
<DT STYLE='FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;MARGIN-BOTTOM:-9PT;'>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:6PT;POSITION:RELATIVE;TOP:-2PT;ADD_SUP:2PT;">
	(a)
</FONT>
</FONT>
</DT>
<DD STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
	Represents
	100&nbsp;percent of Northern Border's contractual obligations.
</FONT>
</DD>
</DL>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<I>
	Senior Notes
</I>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	All of Northern Border's outstanding debt securities are senior unsecured notes with similar terms except for interest rates, maturity dates and prepayment premiums. The
	indentures for the notes do not limit the amount of unsecured debt Northern Border may incur, but do restrict secured indebtedness. At December&nbsp;31, 2015, Northern Border was in compliance with
	all of its financial covenants.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	At
	December&nbsp;31, 2015, the aggregate estimated fair value of Northern Border's long-term debt was approximately $426&nbsp;million
	(2014&nbsp;&#150;&nbsp;$476&nbsp;million). In 2015, interest expense related to the senior notes was $25&nbsp;million
	(2014&nbsp;&#150;&nbsp;$25&nbsp;million; 2013&nbsp;&#150;&nbsp;$25&nbsp;million).
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<I>
	Credit Agreement
</I>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	Northern Border's credit agreement consists of a $200&nbsp;million revolving credit facility. On October&nbsp;9, 2015 Northern Border's credit facility was renewed and
	extended for an additional five years maturing on October&nbsp;9, 2020. At December&nbsp;31, 2015, $61&nbsp;million was outstanding leaving $139&nbsp;million available for future borrowings.
	At Northern Border's option, the interest rate on the outstanding borrowings may be the lenders' base rate or LIBOR plus, in either case, an applicable margin that is based on Northern Border's
	long-term unsecured credit ratings. The interest rate on Northern Border's credit agreement at December&nbsp;31, 2015 was 1.74&nbsp;percent
	(2014&nbsp;&#150;&nbsp;1.39&nbsp;percent). At December&nbsp;31, 2015, Northern Border was in compliance with all of its financial covenants.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<I>
	Operating Leases
</I>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	Northern Border is required to make future minimum payments for office space and rights-of-way under non-cancelable operating leases.
</FONT>
</P>
<EFX_UNIDENTIFIED_TABLE>

<DL COMPACT>
<DT STYLE='FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;MARGIN-BOTTOM:-9PT;'>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:6PT;POSITION:RELATIVE;TOP:-2PT;ADD_SUP:2PT;">
	(a)
</FONT>
</FONT>
</DT>
<DD STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
	Represents
	100&nbsp;percent of Great Lakes' contractual obligations.
</FONT>
</DD>
</DL>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<I>
	Long-Term Financing
</I>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	All of Great Lakes' outstanding debt securities are senior unsecured notes with similar terms except for interest rates, maturity dates and prepayment premiums.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	Great
	Lakes is required to comply with certain financial, operational and legal covenants. Under the most restrictive covenants in the senior note agreements, approximately
	$160&nbsp;million of Great Lakes' partners' capital was restricted as to distributions as of December&nbsp;31, 2015 (2014&nbsp;&#150;&nbsp;$170&nbsp;million). Great Lakes
	was in compliance with all of its financial covenants at December&nbsp;31,&nbsp;2015.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	The
	aggregate estimated fair value of Great Lakes' long-term debt was $362&nbsp;million at December&nbsp;31, 2015
	(2014&nbsp;&#150;&nbsp;$409&nbsp;million). The aggregate annual required repayment of senior notes is $19&nbsp;million for each year 2016 through 2018 and $21&nbsp;million
	for each year 2019 and 2020. Aggregate required
	repayments of senior notes thereafter total $198&nbsp;million. In 2015, interest expense related to Great Lakes' senior notes was $24&nbsp;million
	(2014&nbsp;&#150;&nbsp;$25&nbsp;million; 2013&nbsp;&#150;&nbsp;$27&nbsp;million).
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<I>
	Other
</I>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	Great Lakes has a cash management agreement with TransCanada whereby Great Lakes' funds are pooled with other TransCanada affiliates. The agreement also gives Great Lakes the
	ability to obtain short-term borrowings to provide liquidity for Great Lakes' operating needs.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<B>
<!-- COMMAND=ADD_TXTHEX,"PMS287" -->
</B>
</FONT>
<FONT COLOR="#0C2E82" SIZE=2>
<B>
	Cash Distribution Policy of the Partnership
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	The following table illustrates the percentage allocations of available cash from operating surplus between the common unitholders and our General Partner based on the
	specified target distribution levels. The percentage interests set forth below for our General Partner include its two percent general partner interest and IDRs, and assume our General Partner has
	contributed any additional capital necessary to maintain its two percent general partner interest. The distribution to the General Partner illustrated below, other than in its capacity as a holder of
	5,797,106&nbsp;common units that are in excess of its effective two percent general partner interest, represents the&nbsp;IDRs.
</FONT>
</P>

<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<I>
	2015 Fourth Quarter Cash Distribution
</I>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	On January&nbsp;21, 2016, the board of directors of our General Partner declared the Partnership's fourth quarter 2015 cash distribution in the amount of $0.89 per common
	unit. The fourth quarter cash distribution, which was paid on February&nbsp;12, 2016 to unitholders of record as of February&nbsp;2, 2016, totaled $59&nbsp;million and was paid in the following
	manner: $57&nbsp;million to common unitholders (including $5&nbsp;million to the General Partner as holder of 5,797,106&nbsp;common units and $10&nbsp;million to another subsidiary of
	TransCanada as holder of 11,287,725&nbsp;common units) and $2&nbsp;million to the General Partner in respect of its two percent general partner interest and incentive distributions.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	For
	the year ending December&nbsp;31, 2015, the total cash distribution declared by the board of directors of our General Partner was $3.51 per common&nbsp;unit.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	Please
	read Note&nbsp;13, which provides a summary information schedule regarding our distributions within Part&nbsp;IV, Item&nbsp;15. "Exhibits and Financial
	Statements Schedules".
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<I>
	Distributions to Class&nbsp;B Units
</I>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	The Class&nbsp;B units issued on April&nbsp;1, 2015 represent limited partner interests in us and entitle TransCanada to an annual distribution which is an amount based on
	30&nbsp;percent of GTN's annual distributions after achieving certain annual thresholds.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	During
	the current year, such threshold was exceeded. As a result, on January&nbsp;21, 2016, the board of directors of our General Partner declared distributions to the
	Class&nbsp;B unitholders in the amount of $12&nbsp;million which amount was paid on February&nbsp;12,&nbsp;2016.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	Please
	read Notes&nbsp;6, 9 and&nbsp;12 within Part&nbsp;IV, Item&nbsp;15. "Exhibits and Financial Statements Schedules" and Part&nbsp;II, Item&nbsp;7.
	"Management Discussion and Analysis of Financial Condition and Results of Operations&nbsp;&#150;&nbsp;Liquidity and Capital
	Resources&nbsp;&#150;&nbsp;Issuance of Class&nbsp;B Units to TransCanada."
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<I>
	Distribution Policies of Our Pipeline Systems
</I>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	Distributions of available cash are made to partners on a pro&nbsp;rata basis according to each partner's ownership percentage, approximately one month following the end of a
	quarter. Our pipeline systems' respective management committees determine the amounts and timing of cash distributions, where the amounts of such distributions are based on distributable cash flow as
	determined by a prescribed formula. Any changes to, or suspension of our pipeline systems' cash distribution policies requires the unanimous approval of their respective management committees.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	GTN,
	Bison, and North Baja's distribution policies require the pipelines to distribute 100&nbsp;percent of distributable cash flow based on earnings before depreciation
	and amortization less allowance for funds used during construction (AFUDC) and maintenance capital expenditures. This defined formula is subject to management committee approval and can be modified to
	ensure minimum cash balances, equity balances and ratios are&nbsp;maintained.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	Tuscarora's
	distribution policy requires the distribution of 100&nbsp;percent of distributable cash flow based on earnings before depreciation and amortization less debt
	repayment, AFUDC and maintenance capital expenditures. This defined
</FONT>
</P>
<P ALIGN="RIGHT" STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<B>
<!-- COMMAND=ADD_TXTHEX,"PMS287" -->
</B>
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
	2015 ANNUAL
	REPORT&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
<!-- COMMAND=ADD_TXTHEX,"PMS287" -->
</FONT>
<FONT COLOR="#0C2E82" SIZE=1>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
<B>
<!-- COMMAND=ADD_TXTHEX,"PMS287" -->
</B>
</FONT>
<FONT COLOR="#0C2E82" SIZE=2>
<B>
	53
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
<HR NOSHADE>
<P STYLE='FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE:ALWAYS'>
</P>
<!-- ZEQ.=3,SEQ=53,EFW="2227406",CP="TC PIPELINES, LP",DN="1",CHK=181346,FOLIO='53',FILE='DISK132:[15ZCW1.15ZCW77001]DM77001A.;12',USER='RRICKEN',CD='25-FEB-2016;13:00' -->
<A NAME="A2227406Z10-K_HTM_PAGE_DM77001_1_54">
</A>
<BR>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	formula
	is subject to management committee approval and can be modified to ensure minimum cash balances, equity balances and ratios are&nbsp;maintained.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	Northern
	Border's distribution policy requires Northern Border to distribute 100&nbsp;percent of the distributable cash flow based on earnings before interest, taxes,
	depreciation and amortization less interest expense and maintenance capital expenditures. Northern Border adopted certain changes related to equity contributions that defined minimum equity to total
	capitalization ratios to be used by the Northern Border management committee to determine the amount of required equity contributions, timing of the required contributions and for any shortfall due to
	the inability to refinance maturing debt to be funded by equity contributions.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	Great
	Lakes' distribution policy requires the distribution of 100&nbsp;percent of distributable cash flow based on earnings before income taxes, depreciation, AFUDC less
	capital expenditures and debt repayments not funded with cash calls to its partners. This defined formula is subject to management committee approval and can be modified to ensure minimum cash
	balances, equity balances and ratios are&nbsp;maintained.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	PNGTS
	distributes its available cash less any required reserves that are necessary to comply with its debt covenants and/or appropriately conduct its business, as determined
	and approved by its management committee.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<B>
<!-- COMMAND=ADD_TXTHEX,"PMS287" -->
</B>
</FONT>
<FONT COLOR="#0C2E82" SIZE=2>
<B>
	Cash from Our Pipeline Systems
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	Northern Border declared its fourth quarter 2015 distribution of $44&nbsp;million on January&nbsp;11, 2016, of which the Partnership received its 50&nbsp;percent share or
	$22&nbsp;million. The distribution was paid on February&nbsp;1,&nbsp;2016.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	Great
	Lakes declared its fourth quarter 2015 distribution of $42&nbsp;million on January&nbsp;11, 2016, of which the Partnership received its 46.45&nbsp;percent share
	or $20&nbsp;million. The distribution was paid on February&nbsp;1,&nbsp;2016.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	The
	Partnership's equity investee PNGTS has $22&nbsp;million of senior secured notes due in 2016, of which the Partnership's share is approximately $11&nbsp;million.
	While PNGTS debt repayments are not funded with cash calls to its owners, PNGTS has historically funded its scheduled debt repayments by adjusting its available cash for distribution, which
	effectively reduces the net cash that will be received by the Partnership as distributions from&nbsp;PNGTS.
</FONT>
</P>

<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<I>
	Other Investing Activities
</I>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	In 2016, our pipeline systems expect to invest approximately $48&nbsp;million in maintenance of existing facilities and approximately $15&nbsp;million in growth projects,
	of which the Partnership's share would be $33&nbsp;million and $10&nbsp;million, respectively.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<B>
<!-- COMMAND=ADD_TXTHEX,"PMS287" -->
</B>
</FONT>
<FONT COLOR="#0C2E82" SIZE=2>
<B>
	CRITICAL ACCOUNTING ESTIMATES
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	The preparation of financial statements in accordance with GAAP requires us to make estimates and assumptions with respect to values or conditions which cannot be known with
	certainty, that affect the reported amount of assets and liabilities and the disclosure of contingent assets and liabilities at the date of the financial statements. Such estimates and assumptions
	also affect the reported amounts of revenue and expenses during the reporting period. Although we believe these estimates and assumptions are reasonable, actual results could&nbsp;differ.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	We
	believe our critical accounting estimates discussed in the following paragraphs require us to make the most significant assumptions when preparing our financial
	statements and changes in these assumptions could have a material impact on the financial statements. These critical accounting estimates should be read in conjunction with Note&nbsp;2 of
	Part&nbsp;IV, Item&nbsp;15. "Exhibits and Financial Statement Schedules."
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	We
	account for our investments in Northern Border and Great Lakes using the equity method of accounting. The equity method of accounting is appropriate where the investor
	does not control an investee, but rather is able to exercise significant influence over the operating and financial policies of an investee. We are able to exercise significant influence over our
	investments in Northern Border and Great Lakes because of our ownership interests and our representation on their management committees.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	We
	account for our investments in GTN, Bison, North Baja and Tuscarora using the consolidation method, as we are able to exercise control over these investments because of
	our ownership interests and our representation on their management committees.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<B>
<!-- COMMAND=ADD_TXTHEX,"PMS287" -->
</B>
</FONT>
<FONT COLOR="#0C2E82" SIZE=2>
<B>
	Regulation
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	Our pipeline systems' accounting policies conform to
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
<I>
	Accounting Standards Codification (ASC) 980&nbsp;&#150;&nbsp;Regulated
	Operations
</I>
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
	. As a result, our pipeline systems record assets and liabilities that result from the regulated ratemaking process that may not be recorded under GAAP for
	non-regulated entities. Regulatory assets generally represent incurred costs that have been deferred because such costs are probable of future recovery in customer rates. Regulatory liabilities
	generally represent obligations to make refunds to customers or for instances where the regulator provides current rates that are intended to recover costs that are expected to be incurred in the
	future. Our pipeline systems consider several factors to evaluate their continued application of the provisions of ASC 980&nbsp;such as potential deregulation of their pipelines; anticipated changes
	from cost-based ratemaking to another form of regulation; increasing competition that limits their ability to recover costs; and regulatory actions that limit rate relief to a level insufficient to
	recover&nbsp;costs.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	Certain
	assets that result from the ratemaking process are reflected on the balance sheets of our pipeline systems. If it is determined that future recovery of these assets
	is no longer probable as a result of discontinuing application of ASC 980 or other regulatory actions, our pipeline systems would be required to write off the regulatory assets at that&nbsp;time.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	As
	of December&nbsp;31, 2015, Northern Border reflected regulatory assets of $16&nbsp;million on its balance sheet
	(2014&nbsp;&#150;&nbsp;$32&nbsp;million). Northern Border also has regulatory liabilities of $22&nbsp;million as of December&nbsp;31, 2015
	(2014&nbsp;&#150;&nbsp;$20&nbsp;million).
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	As
	of December&nbsp;31, 2015 and 2014, Great Lakes did not have any material regulatory assets and no material regulatory liabilities recorded on its balance&nbsp;sheet.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	At
	December&nbsp;31, 2015, the Partnership had $2&nbsp;million regulatory assets reported as part of accounts receivable and other in the balance sheet representing
	volumetric fuel tracker assets that are settled with in-kind exchanges with
</FONT>
</P>
<P ALIGN="RIGHT" STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<B>
<!-- COMMAND=ADD_TXTHEX,"PMS287" -->
</B>
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
	2015 ANNUAL
	REPORT&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
<!-- COMMAND=ADD_TXTHEX,"PMS287" -->
</FONT>
<FONT COLOR="#0C2E82" SIZE=1>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
<B>
<!-- COMMAND=ADD_TXTHEX,"PMS287" -->
</B>
</FONT>
<FONT COLOR="#0C2E82" SIZE=2>
<B>
	55
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
