<DL COMPACT>
<DT STYLE='FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;MARGIN-BOTTOM:-9PT;'>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:6PT;POSITION:RELATIVE;TOP:-2PT;ADD_SUP:2PT;">
	(a)
</FONT>
</FONT>
</DT>
<DD STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
	$200&nbsp;thousand
	of the 2015 and 2014 Audit Fees relate to ATM equity financing and $150&nbsp;thousand of the 2015 Audit Fees relate to issuance of
	senior unsecured notes in connection with 2015 GTN Acquisition.
<BR>
<BR>
</FONT>
</DD>
<DT STYLE='FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;MARGIN-BOTTOM:-9PT;'>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:6PT;POSITION:RELATIVE;TOP:-2PT;ADD_SUP:2PT;">
	(b)
</FONT>
</FONT>
</DT>
<DD STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
	Includes
	Advisory services for Class&nbsp;B issuance amounting to $26&nbsp;thousand.
<BR>
<BR>
</FONT>
</DD>
<DT STYLE='FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;MARGIN-BOTTOM:-9PT;'>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:6PT;POSITION:RELATIVE;TOP:-2PT;ADD_SUP:2PT;">
	(c)
</FONT>
</FONT>
</DT>
<DD STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
	The
	Partnership did not engage its external auditors for any tax or other services in 2015 or&nbsp;2014.
</FONT>
</DD>
</DL>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<B>
<!-- COMMAND=ADD_TXTHEX,"PMS287" -->
</B>
</FONT>
<FONT COLOR="#0C2E82" SIZE=2>
<B>
	AUDIT FEES
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	Audit fees include fees for the audit of annual GAAP financial statements, reviews of the related quarterly financial statements and related consents and comfort letters for
	documents filed with the SEC. Before our independent registered public accounting firm is engaged each year for annual audit and any non-audit services, these services and fees are reviewed and
	approved by our Audit Committee.
</FONT>
</P>

<EFX_AUDITORS_OPINION>
<A NAME="FIS_AUDITORS_OPINION"></A>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<!-- COMMAND=ADD_BASECOLOR,"BLACK" -->
<!-- COMMAND=ADD_DEFAULTFONT,"FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;" -->
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
<B>
<!-- COMMAND=ADD_TXTHEX,"PMS287" -->
</B>
</FONT>
<FONT COLOR="#0C2E82" SIZE=2>
<B>
	REPORT OF INDEPENDENT REGISTERED PUBLIC ACCOUNTING FIRM
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<B>
	The Board of Directors and Unitholders
<BR>
	TC&nbsp;PipeLines&nbsp;GP,&nbsp;Inc. General Partner of TC&nbsp;PipeLines,&nbsp;LP:
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	We have audited the accompanying consolidated balance sheets of TC&nbsp;PipeLines,&nbsp;LP (a&nbsp;Delaware limited partnership) and
	subsidiaries as of December&nbsp;31, 2015 and 2014, and the related consolidated statements of income, comprehensive income, cash flows and changes in partners' equity for each of the years in the
	three-year period ended December&nbsp;31, 2015. We also have audited TC&nbsp;PipeLines,&nbsp;LP's internal control over financial reporting as of December&nbsp;31, 2015, based on criteria
	established in
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
<I>
	Internal Control&nbsp;&#150;&nbsp;Integrated Framework (2013)
</I>
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
	issued by the Committee of Sponsoring Organizations
	of the Treadway Commission (COSO). Management of the General Partner of TC&nbsp;PipeLines,&nbsp;LP is responsible for these consolidated financial statements, for maintaining effective internal
	control over financial reporting, and for its assessment of the effectiveness of internal control over financial reporting, included in the accompanying Management's Annual Report on Internal Control
	over Financial Reporting. Our responsibility is to express an opinion on these consolidated financial statements and an opinion on TC&nbsp;PipeLines,&nbsp;LP's internal control over financial
	reporting based on our&nbsp;audits.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	We
	conducted our audits in accordance with the standards of the Public Company Accounting Oversight Board (United&nbsp;States). Those standards require that we plan and
	perform the audits to obtain reasonable assurance about whether the financial statements are free of material misstatement and whether effective internal control over financial reporting was
	maintained in all material respects. Our audits of the consolidated financial statements included examining, on a test basis, evidence supporting the amounts and disclosures in the financial
	statements, assessing the accounting principles used and significant estimates made by management, and evaluating the overall financial statement presentation. Our audit of internal control over
	financial reporting included obtaining an understanding of internal control over financial reporting, assessing the risk that a material weakness exists, and testing
	and evaluating the design and operating effectiveness of internal control based on the assessed risk. Our audits also included performing such other procedures as we considered necessary in the
	circumstances. We believe that our audits provide a reasonable basis for our&nbsp;opinions.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	A
	company's internal control over financial reporting is a process designed to provide reasonable assurance regarding the reliability of financial reporting and the
	preparation of financial statements for external purposes in accordance with generally accepted accounting principles. A company's internal control over financial reporting includes those policies and
	procedures that (1)&nbsp;pertain to the maintenance of records that, in reasonable detail, accurately and fairly reflect the transactions and dispositions of the assets of the company;
	(2)&nbsp;provide reasonable assurance that transactions are recorded as necessary to permit preparation of financial statements in accordance with generally accepted accounting principles, and that
	receipts and expenditures of the company are being made only in accordance with authorizations of management and directors of the company; and (3)&nbsp;provide reasonable assurance regarding
	prevention or timely detection of unauthorized acquisition, use, or disposition of the Partnership's assets that could have a material effect on the financial statements.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	Because
	of its inherent limitations, internal control over financial reporting may not prevent or detect misstatements. Also, projections of any evaluation of effectiveness
	to future periods are subject to the risk that controls may become inadequate because of changes in conditions, or that the degree of compliance with the policies or procedures may deteriorate.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	In
	our opinion, the consolidated financial statements referred to above present fairly, in all material respects, the financial position of TC&nbsp;PipeLines,&nbsp;LP
	and subsidiaries as of December&nbsp;31, 2015 and 2014, and the results of their operations and their cash flows for each of the years in the three-year period ended December&nbsp;31, 2015, in
	conformity with U.S.&nbsp;generally accepted accounting principles. Also in our opinion, TC&nbsp;PipeLines,&nbsp;LP maintained, in all material respects, effective internal control over
	financial reporting as of December&nbsp;31, 2015, based on criteria established in
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
<I>
	Internal Control&nbsp;&#150;&nbsp;Integrated Framework
	(2013)
</I>
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
	issued by the Committee of Sponsoring Organizations of the Treadway Commission (COSO).
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	/s/
	KPMG&nbsp;LLP
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	Houston,
	Texas
<BR>
	February&nbsp;26, 2016
</FONT>
</P>
</EFX_AUDITORS_OPINION>

<DT STYLE='FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;MARGIN-BOTTOM:-9PT;'>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:6PT;POSITION:RELATIVE;TOP:-2PT;ADD_SUP:2PT;">
	(a)
</FONT>
</FONT>
</DT>
<DD STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
	Losses
	related to cash flow hedges reported in Accumulated Other Comprehensive Loss and expected to be reclassified to net income in the next
	12&nbsp;months are estimated to be $1&nbsp;million. These estimates assume constant interest rates over time; however, the amounts reclassified will vary based on actual value of interest rates at
	the date of&nbsp;settlement.
<BR>
<BR>
</FONT>
</DD>
<DT STYLE='FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;MARGIN-BOTTOM:-9PT;'>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:6PT;POSITION:RELATIVE;TOP:-2PT;ADD_SUP:2PT;">
	(b)
</FONT>
</FONT>
</DT>
<DD STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
	Recast
	as discussed in Note&nbsp;2 and Note&nbsp;6.

<FONT COLOR="#0C2E82" SIZE=1>
<B>
	NOTE 1&nbsp;ORGANIZATION
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
	TC&nbsp;PipeLines,&nbsp;LP and its subsidiaries are collectively referred to herein as the Partnership. The Partnership was formed by TransCanada PipeLines Limited, a
	wholly-owned subsidiary of TransCanada Corporation (TransCanada Corporation together with its subsidiaries collectively referred to herein as TransCanada), to acquire, own and participate in the
	management of energy infrastructure assets in North&nbsp;America.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
	The
	Partnership owns the following interests in natural gas pipeline systems:
</FONT>
</P>

	(a)

</DT>

<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
	Effective
	January&nbsp;1, 2016 (Refer to Note&nbsp;22)
</FONT>
</DD>

<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
	The
	Partnership is managed by its General Partner, TC PipeLines&nbsp;GP,&nbsp;Inc. (General Partner), an indirect wholly-owned subsidiary of TransCanada. The General
	Partner provides management and operating services for the Partnership and is reimbursed for its costs and expenses. The General Partner owns 5,797,106&nbsp;common units, 100&nbsp;percent of our
	IDRs and an effective two percent general partner interest in the Partnership at December&nbsp;31, 2015. TransCanada also indirectly holds an additional 11,287,725&nbsp;common units, for total
	ownership of 26.6&nbsp;percent of our outstanding common units and 100&nbsp;percent of our Class&nbsp;B units at December&nbsp;31, 2015 (Refer to Note&nbsp;6).
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
<B>
<!-- COMMAND=ADD_TXTHEX,"PMS287" -->
</B>
</FONT>
<FONT COLOR="#0C2E82" SIZE=1>
<B>
	NOTE 2&nbsp;SIGNIFICANT ACCOUNTING POLICIES
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
	The accompanying financial statements and related notes have been prepared in accordance with United&nbsp;States generally accepted accounting principles (GAAP) and amounts
	are stated in U.S.&nbsp;dollars. The financial statements and notes present the financial position of the Partnership as of December&nbsp;31, 2015 and 2014 and the results of its operations, cash
	flows and changes in partners' equity for the years ended December&nbsp;31, 2015, 2014 and&nbsp;2013.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
<B>
<!-- COMMAND=ADD_TXTHEX,"PMS287" -->
</B>
</FONT>

<B>

</B>
</FONT>

<!-- ZEQ.=1,SEQ=88,EFW="2227406",CP="TC PIPELINES, LP",DN="1",CHK=921890,FOLIO='F-7',FILE='DISK132:[15ZCW1.15ZCW77001]FG77001A.;18',USER='PFERGUSA',CD='23-FEB-2016;22:09' -->
<A NAME="A2227406Z10-K_HTM_PAGE_FG77001_1_8">
</A>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
<B>
<!-- COMMAND=ADD_TXTHEX,"PMS287" -->
</B>
</FONT>
<FONT COLOR="#0C2E82" SIZE=1>
<B>
	(a)&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Basis of Presentation
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
	The Partnership consolidates its investments in GTN, Bison, North Baja and Tuscarora, over which it is able to exercise control. To the extent there are interests owned by other
	parties, these interests are included in non-controlling interests. The Partnership uses the equity method of accounting for its investments in Northern Border and Great Lakes, over which it is able
	to exercise significant influence.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
	On
	April&nbsp;1, 2015 and October&nbsp;1, 2014, the Partnership acquired the remaining 30&nbsp;percent interest in GTN and Bison, respectively, from subsidiaries of
	TransCanada. These acquisitions resulted in GTN and Bison being wholly-owned by the Partnership. Prior to these transactions, the remaining 30&nbsp;percent interests held by subsidiaries of
	TransCanada were reflected as non-controlling interests in the Partnership's consolidated financial statements. The acquisitions of these already-consolidated entities were accounted as a transaction
	between entities under common control, similar to a pooling of interests, whereby the acquired interests were recorded at TransCanada's carrying value and the total excess purchase price paid was
	recorded as a reduction in Partners' Equity. Refer to Note&nbsp;6 for additional disclosures regarding these acquisitions.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
	On
	July&nbsp;1, 2013, the Partnership acquired a 45&nbsp;percent membership interest in each of GTN and Bison (the&nbsp;2013 Acquisition) from subsidiaries of
	TransCanada increasing the Partnership's ownership in each of GTN and Bison to 70&nbsp;percent. The 2013 Acquisition was accounted for as a transaction between entities under common control, similar
	to a pooling of interests, whereby the assets and liabilities of GTN and Bison were recorded at TransCanada's carrying value and the Partnership's historical financial information, except net income
	per common unit, was recast to consolidate GTN and Bison for all periods presented. Refer to Note&nbsp;6 for additional disclosure regarding the 2013 Acquisition.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
<B>
<!-- COMMAND=ADD_TXTHEX,"PMS287" -->
</B>
</FONT>
<FONT COLOR="#0C2E82" SIZE=1>
<B>
	(b)&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Use of Estimates
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
	The preparation of financial statements requires management to make estimates and assumptions that affect the reported amounts of assets and liabilities and disclosure of
	contingent assets and liabilities as of the date of the financial statements and the reported amounts of revenues and expenses during the reporting period. Although management believes these estimates
	are reasonable, actual results could differ from these estimates.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
<B>
<!-- COMMAND=ADD_TXTHEX,"PMS287" -->
</B>
</FONT>
<FONT COLOR="#0C2E82" SIZE=1>
<B>
	(c)&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Cash and Cash Equivalents
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
	The Partnership's cash and cash equivalents consist of cash and highly liquid short-term investments with original maturities of three months or less and are recorded at cost,
	which approximates fair&nbsp;value.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
<B>
<!-- COMMAND=ADD_TXTHEX,"PMS287" -->
</B>
</FONT>
<FONT COLOR="#0C2E82" SIZE=1>
<B>
	(d)&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Trade Accounts Receivable
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
	Trade accounts receivable are recorded at the invoiced amount and do not bear interest. We review our accounts receivable regularly and record allowances for doubtful accounts
	using the specific identification method.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
<B>
<!-- COMMAND=ADD_TXTHEX,"PMS287" -->
</B>
</FONT>
<FONT COLOR="#0C2E82" SIZE=1>
<B>
	(e)&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Inventories
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
	Inventories primarily consist of materials and supplies and are carried at the lower of weighted average cost or&nbsp;market.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
<B>
<!-- COMMAND=ADD_TXTHEX,"PMS287" -->
</B>
</FONT>
<FONT COLOR="#0C2E82" SIZE=1>
<B>
	(f)&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Plant, Property and Equipment
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
	Plant, property and equipment are stated at original cost. Costs of restoring the land above and around the pipeline are capitalized to pipeline facilities and depreciated over
	the remaining life of the related pipeline facilities. Pipeline facilities and compression equipment have an estimated useful life of 20 to 77&nbsp;years and metering and other equipment ranges from
	5 to 77&nbsp;years. Depreciation is calculated on a straight-line composite basis over the assets' estimated useful lives. Repair and maintenance costs are expensed as incurred. Costs that are
	considered a betterment are capitalized.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
	An
	allowance for funds used during construction, using the rate of return on rate base approved by the Federal Energy Regulatory Commission (FERC), is capitalized and
	included in the cost of plant, property and equipment. Amounts included in construction work in progress are not amortized until transferred into&nbsp;service.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
<B>
<!-- COMMAND=ADD_TXTHEX,"PMS287" -->
</B>
</FONT>
<FONT COLOR="#0C2E82" SIZE=1>
<B>
	(g)&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Impairment of Equity Method Investments
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
	We review our equity method investments when a significant event or change in circumstances has occurred that may have an adverse effect on the fair value of each investment.
	When such events or changes occur, we compare the estimated fair value to the carrying value of the related investment. We calculate the estimated fair value of an investment in an equity method
	investee using an income approach and market approach. The development of fair value estimates requires significant judgment including estimates of future cash flows, which is dependent on internal
	forecasts, estimates of the long-term rate of growth for the investee, estimates of the useful life over which cash flows will occur, and determination of weighted average cost of capital. The
	estimates used to calculate the fair value of an investee can change
</FONT>
</P>
<P ALIGN="RIGHT" STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
<B>
<!-- COMMAND=ADD_TXTHEX,"PMS287" -->
</B>
</FONT>
<FONT COLOR="#0C2E82" SIZE=1>
<B>
	F-8
</B>
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;2015
	ANNUAL REPORT
</FONT>
</P>
<HR NOSHADE>
<P STYLE='FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE:ALWAYS'>
</P>
<!-- ZEQ.=2,SEQ=89,EFW="2227406",CP="TC PIPELINES, LP",DN="1",CHK=478668,FOLIO='F-8',FILE='DISK132:[15ZCW1.15ZCW77001]FG77001A.;18',USER='PFERGUSA',CD='23-FEB-2016;22:09' -->
<A NAME="A2227406Z10-K_HTM_PAGE_FG77001_1_9">
</A>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
	from
	year to year based on operating results and market conditions. Changes in these estimates and assumptions could materially affect the determination of fair value and our assessment as to whether
	an investment in an equity method investee has suffered an&nbsp;impairment.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
	If
	the estimated fair value of an investment is less than its carrying value, we are required to determine if the decline in fair value is other than temporary. This
	determination considers the aforementioned valuation methodologies, the length of time and the extent to which fair value has been less than carrying value, the financial condition and near-term
	prospects of the investee, including any specific events which may influence the operations of the investee, the intent and ability of the holder to retain its investment in the investee for a period
	of time sufficient to allow for any anticipated recovery in market value, and other facts and circumstances. If the fair value of an investment is less than its carrying value and the decline in value
	is determined to be other than temporary, we record an impairment charge.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
	During
	the fourth quarter of 2015, we recognized an impairment charge on our investment in Great Lakes amounting to $199&nbsp;million (See&nbsp;Note&nbsp;4 for further
	information).
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
<B>
<!-- COMMAND=ADD_TXTHEX,"PMS287" -->
</B>
</FONT>
<FONT COLOR="#0C2E82" SIZE=1>
<B>
	(h)&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Impairment of Long-lived Assets
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
	The Partnership reviews long-lived assets, such as plant, property and equipment for impairment whenever events or changes in circumstances indicate the carrying value may not
	be recoverable. If the total of the estimated undiscounted future cash flows is less than the carrying value of the assets, an impairment loss is recognized for the excess of the carrying value over
	the fair value of the&nbsp;assets.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
<B>
<!-- COMMAND=ADD_TXTHEX,"PMS287" -->
</B>
</FONT>
<FONT COLOR="#0C2E82" SIZE=1>
<B>
	(i)&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Partners' Equity
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
	Costs incurred in connection with the issuance of units are deducted from the proceeds received.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
<B>
<!-- COMMAND=ADD_TXTHEX,"PMS287" -->
</B>
</FONT>
<FONT COLOR="#0C2E82" SIZE=1>
<B>
	(j)&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Revenue Recognition
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
	Transmission revenues are recognized in the period in which the service is provided. When a rate case is pending final FERC approval, a portion of the revenue collected is
	subject to possible refund. As of December&nbsp;31, 2015, 2014 and 2013, the Partnership has not recognized any transmission revenue that is subject to possible refund.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
<B>
<!-- COMMAND=ADD_TXTHEX,"PMS287" -->
</B>
</FONT>
<FONT COLOR="#0C2E82" SIZE=1>
<B>
	(k)&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Income Taxes
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
	The Partnership is not subject to federal or state income tax. The tax effect of the Partnership's activities accrues to its partners. The Partnership's taxable income or loss,
	which may vary substantially from the net income or loss reported in the consolidated statement of income, is includable in the federal income tax returns of each partner. The aggregate difference in
	the basis of the Partnership's net assets for financial and income tax purposes cannot be readily determined because all information regarding each partner's tax attributes related to the partnership
	is not&nbsp;available.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
<B>
<!-- COMMAND=ADD_TXTHEX,"PMS287" -->
</B>
</FONT>
<FONT COLOR="#0C2E82" SIZE=1>
<B>
	(l)&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Acquisitions and Goodwill
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
	The Partnership accounts for business acquisitions from third parties using the acquisition method of accounting and, accordingly, the assets and liabilities of the acquired
	entities are recorded at their estimated fair values at the date of acquisition. The excess of the purchase price over the fair value of net assets acquired is attributed to goodwill. Goodwill is not
	amortized and is tested on an annual basis for impairment or more frequently if any indicators of impairment are evident. The Partnership initially assesses qualitative factors to determine whether
	events or changes in circumstances indicate that the goodwill might be impaired. If the Partnership does not conclude that it is more likely than not that fair value of the reporting unit is greater
	than its carrying value, the first step of the two-step impairment test is performed by comparing the fair value of the reporting unit to its book value, which includes goodwill. If the fair value is
	less than book value, an impairment is indicated and a second step is performed to measure the amount of the impairment. In the second step, the implied fair value of goodwill is calculated by
	deducting the recognized amounts of all tangible and intangible net assets of the reporting unit from the fair value determined in the initial assessment. If the carrying value of goodwill exceeds the
	calculated implied fair value of goodwill, an impairment charge is&nbsp;recorded.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
	The
	Partnership accounts for business acquisitions between itself and TransCanada as transactions between entities under common control. Using this approach, the assets and
	liabilities of the acquired entities are recorded at TransCanada's carrying value. In the event recasting is required, the Partnership's historical financial information will be recast, except net
	income per common unit, to include the acquired entities for all periods presented. If the fair market value paid for the acquired entities is greater than the recorded net assets of the acquired
	entities, the excess purchase price paid is recorded as a reduction in Partners' Equity. Similarly, if the fair market value paid for the acquired entities is less than the recorded net assets of the
	acquired entities, the excess of assets acquired is recorded as an increase in Partners' Equity.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
<B>
<!-- COMMAND=ADD_TXTHEX,"PMS287" -->
</B>
</FONT>
<FONT COLOR="#0C2E82" SIZE=1>
<B>
	F-9
</B>
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;TC
	PIPELINES, LP
</FONT>
</P>

<!-- ZEQ.=3,SEQ=90,EFW="2227406",CP="TC PIPELINES, LP",DN="1",CHK=401880,FOLIO='F-9',FILE='DISK132:[15ZCW1.15ZCW77001]FG77001A.;18',USER='PFERGUSA',CD='23-FEB-2016;22:09' -->
<A NAME="A2227406Z10-K_HTM_PAGE_FG77001_1_10">
</A>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
<B>
<!-- COMMAND=ADD_TXTHEX,"PMS287" -->
</B>
</FONT>
<FONT COLOR="#0C2E82" SIZE=1>
<B>
	(m)&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Fair Value Measurements
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
	For cash and cash equivalents, receivables, accounts payable, certain accrued expenses and short-term debt, the carrying amount approximates fair value due to the short
	maturities of these instruments. For long-term debt instruments and the interest rate swap agreements, fair value is estimated based upon market values (if&nbsp;applicable) or on the current
	interest rates available to us for debt with similar terms and remaining maturities. Considerable judgment is required in developing these estimates.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
<B>
<!-- COMMAND=ADD_TXTHEX,"PMS287" -->
</B>
</FONT>
<FONT COLOR="#0C2E82" SIZE=1>
<B>
	(n)&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Derivative Financial Instruments and Hedging Activities
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
	The Partnership recognizes all derivative instruments as either assets or liabilities in the balance sheet at their respective fair values. For derivatives designated in hedging
	relationships, changes in the fair value are either offset through earnings against the change in fair value of the hedged item attributable to the risk being hedged or recognized in accumulated other
	comprehensive income, to the extent the derivative is effective at offsetting the changes in cash flows being hedged until the hedged item affects earnings.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
	The
	Partnership only enters into derivative contracts that it intends to designate as a hedge of a forecasted transaction or the variability of cash flows to be received or
	paid related to a recognized asset or liability (cash flow hedge). For all hedging relationships, the Partnership formally documents the hedging relationship and its risk management objective and
	strategy for undertaking the hedge, the hedging instrument, the hedged transaction, the nature of the risk being hedged, how the hedging instrument's effectiveness in offsetting the hedged risk will
	be assessed prospectively and retrospectively, and a description of the method used to measure ineffectiveness. The Partnership also formally assesses, both at the inception of the hedging
	relationship and on an ongoing basis, whether the derivatives that are used in hedging relationships are highly effective in offsetting changes in cash flows of hedged transactions. For derivative
	instruments that are designated and qualify as part of a cash flow hedging relationship, the effective portion of the gain or loss on the derivative is reported as a component of other comprehensive
	income and reclassified into earnings in the same period or periods during which the hedged transaction affects earnings. Gains and losses on the derivative representing either hedge ineffectiveness
	or hedge components excluded from the assessment of effectiveness are recognized in current earnings.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
	The
	Partnership discontinues hedge accounting prospectively when it determines that the derivative is no longer effective in offsetting cash flows attributable to the hedged
	risk, the derivative expires or is sold, terminated, or exercised, the cash flow hedge is de-designated because a forecasted transaction is not probable of occurring, or management determines to
	remove the designation of the cash flow&nbsp;hedge.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
	In
	all situations in which hedge accounting is discontinued and the derivative remains outstanding, the Partnership continues to carry the derivative at its fair value on
	the balance sheet and recognizes any subsequent changes in its fair value in earnings. When it is probable that a forecasted transaction will not occur, the Partnership discontinues hedge accounting
	and recognizes immediately in earnings gains and losses that were accumulated in other comprehensive income related to the hedging relationship.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
<B>
<!-- COMMAND=ADD_TXTHEX,"PMS287" -->
</B>
</FONT>
<FONT COLOR="#0C2E82" SIZE=1>
<B>
	(o)&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Asset Retirement Obligation
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
	The Partnership recognizes the fair value of a liability for asset retirement obligations in the period in which it is incurred, when a legal obligation exists and a reasonable
	estimate of fair value can be made. The fair value is added to the carrying amount of the associated asset and the liability is accreted through charges to operating expenses.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
	The
	scope and timing of asset retirements related to natural gas pipelines is indeterminable. As a result, the Partnership has recorded no asset retirement obligations as of
	December&nbsp;31, 2015 and&nbsp;2014.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
<B>
<!-- COMMAND=ADD_TXTHEX,"PMS287" -->
</B>
</FONT>
<FONT COLOR="#0C2E82" SIZE=1>
<B>
	(p)&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Government Regulation
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
	The Partnership's subsidiaries are subject to regulation by FERC. Under regulatory accounting principles, certain assets or liabilities that result from the regulated ratemaking
	process may be recorded that would not be recorded under GAAP for non-regulated entities. The timing of recognition of certain revenues and expenses in our regulated business may differ from that
	otherwise expected under GAAP to appropriately reflect the economic impact of the regulators' decisions regarding revenues and rates. The Partnership regularly evaluates the continued applicability of
	regulatory accounting, considering such factors as regulatory changes, the impact of competition, and the ability to recover regulatory assets. At December&nbsp;31, 2015, the Partnership had
	regulatory assets amounting to $2&nbsp;million reported as part of accounts receivable and other in the balance sheet representing volumetric fuel tracker assets that are settled with in-kind
	exchanges with customers continually (2014&nbsp;&#150;&nbsp;nil). Regulatory liabilities are included in other long-term liabilities (refer to Note&nbsp;8). Allowance for
	funds used during construction is capitalized and included in plant, property and&nbsp;equipment.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
<B>
<!-- COMMAND=ADD_TXTHEX,"PMS287" -->
</B>
</FONT>
<FONT COLOR="#0C2E82" SIZE=1>
<B>
	(q)&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Debt Issuance Costs
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
	Costs related to the issuance of debt are deferred and amortized using the effective interest rate method over the term of the related&nbsp;debt.
</FONT>
</P>
<P ALIGN="RIGHT" STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
<B>
<!-- COMMAND=ADD_TXTHEX,"PMS287" -->
</B>
</FONT>
<FONT COLOR="#0C2E82" SIZE=1>
<B>
	F-10
</B>
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;2015
	ANNUAL REPORT
</FONT>
</P>

<!-- ZEQ.=4,SEQ=91,EFW="2227406",CP="TC PIPELINES, LP",DN="1",CHK=538838,FOLIO='F-10',FILE='DISK132:[15ZCW1.15ZCW77001]FG77001A.;18',USER='PFERGUSA',CD='23-FEB-2016;22:09' -->
<A NAME="A2227406Z10-K_HTM_PAGE_FG77001_1_11">
</A>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
<B>
<!-- COMMAND=ADD_TXTHEX,"PMS287" -->
</B>
</FONT>
<FONT COLOR="#0C2E82" SIZE=1>
<B>
	NOTE 3&nbsp;ACCOUNTING PRONOUNCEMENTS NOT YET ADOPTED
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
<B>
<!-- COMMAND=ADD_TXTHEX,"PMS287" -->
</B>
</FONT>
<FONT COLOR="#0C2E82" SIZE=1>
<B>
	Revenue from contracts with customers
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
	In May&nbsp;2014, the Financial Accounting Standards Board (FASB) issued Accounting Standards Update (ASU) No.&nbsp;2014-09 "Revenue from Contracts with Customers (Topic
	606)." This guidance supersedes the revenue recognition requirements in Topic 605, Revenue Recognition and most industry-specific guidance. This new guidance requires that an entity recognizes revenue
	to depict the transfer of promised goods or services to customers in an amount that reflects the consideration to which the company expects to be entitled in exchange for those goods or services. On
	July&nbsp;9, 2015, the FASB voted to defer the effective date by one year to December&nbsp;15, 2017 for annual reporting periods beginning after that date. The FASB also voted to permit early
	adoption of the standard, but not before the original effective date of December&nbsp;15, 2016. This new guidance, once effective, allows two methods in which the amendment can be applied:
	(1)&nbsp;retrospectively to each prior reporting period presented, or (2)&nbsp;retrospectively with the cumulative effect recognized at the date of initial application. The Partnership is
	currently evaluating the impact of the adoption of this ASU and has not yet determined the effect on its consolidated financial statements.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
<B>
<!-- COMMAND=ADD_TXTHEX,"PMS287" -->
</B>
</FONT>
<FONT COLOR="#0C2E82" SIZE=1>
<B>
	Consolidation
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
	In February&nbsp;2015, the FASB issued ASU No.&nbsp;2015-02 "Consolidation (Topic 810)," an amendment of previously issued guidance on consolidation. This updated guidance
	requires that an entity evaluate whether it should consolidate certain legal entities. All legal entities are subject to reevaluation under the revised consolidation model. This guidance is effective
	from January&nbsp;1, 2016 and early application is permitted. Application of this amendment could be performed using a modified retrospective approach by recording a cumulative-effect adjustment to
	equity as of the beginning of the fiscal year of adoption. Alternatively, the amendment could be applied retrospectively. The Partnership is currently evaluating the impact of the adoption of this ASU
	and has not yet determined the effect on its consolidated financial statements.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
<B>
<!-- COMMAND=ADD_TXTHEX,"PMS287" -->
</B>
</FONT>
<FONT COLOR="#0C2E82" SIZE=1>
<B>
	Imputation of interest
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
	In April&nbsp;2015, the FASB issued ASU No.&nbsp;2015-03 "Interest&nbsp;&#150;&nbsp;Imputation of Interest (Subtopic 835-30)," an amendment of
	previously issued guidance on imputation of interest. This updated guidance requires debt issuance costs be presented in the balance sheet as a direct deduction from the carrying amount of debt
	liabilities, consistent with debt discount or premiums. The recognition and measurement for debt issuance costs would not be affected. This guidance is effective from January&nbsp;1, 2016 and early
	application is permitted. This guidance should be adopted on a retrospective basis, wherein the balance sheet of each individual period presented would be adjusted to reflect the period-specific
	effects of applying the new guidance. The application of this amendment will result in a reclassification of debt issuance costs currently recorded in Other Assets to an offset of their respective
	debt liabilities.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
<B>
<!-- COMMAND=ADD_TXTHEX,"PMS287" -->
</B>
</FONT>
<FONT COLOR="#0C2E82" SIZE=1>
<B>
	Earnings Per Share
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
	In April&nbsp;2015, the FASB issued ASU No.&nbsp;2015-06 "Earnings Per Share (Topic 260)," an amendment of previously issued guidance on earnings per share (EPS) as it is
	being calculated by master limited partnerships. This updated guidance specifies that for purposes of calculating historical EPS under the two-class method, the earnings (losses) of a transferred
	business before the date of a dropdown transaction should be allocated entirely to the general partner interest, and previously reported EPS of the limited partners would not change as a result of a
	dropdown transaction. Qualitative disclosures about how the rights to the earnings (losses) differ before and after the dropdown transaction occurs are also required. This guidance is effective from
	January&nbsp;1, 2016 and early application is permitted. This guidance should be adopted on a retrospective basis to all financial statements presented. The Partnership does not expect the adoption
	of this new standard to have a material effect on its consolidated financial statements.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
<B>
<!-- COMMAND=ADD_TXTHEX,"PMS287" -->
</B>
</FONT>
<FONT COLOR="#0C2E82" SIZE=1>
<B>
	Business Combinations
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
	In September&nbsp;2015, the FASB issued ASU No.&nbsp;2015-16 "Business Combinations (Topic 805)," which replaces the requirement that an acquirer in a business combination
	account for measurement period adjustments retrospectively with a requirement that an acquirer recognize adjustments to the provisional amounts that are identified during the measurement period in the
	reporting period in which the adjustment amounts are determined. The amended guidance requires that the acquirer record, in the same period's financial statements, the effect on earnings of changes in
	depreciation, amortization, or other income effects, if any, as a result of the change to the provisional amounts, calculated as if the accounting had been completed at the acquisition date. The new
	guidance is effective January&nbsp;1, 2016 and will be applied prospectively. The Partnership does not expect the adoption of this new standard to have a material effect on its consolidated
	financial statements.
</FONT>
</P>
<EFX_UNIDENTIFIED_TABLE>
<A NAME="FIS_UNIDENTIFIED_TABLE_22"></A>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
<B>
<!-- COMMAND=ADD_TXTHEX,"PMS287" -->
</B>

<DL COMPACT>
<DT STYLE='FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;MARGIN-BOTTOM:-9PT;'>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:6PT;POSITION:RELATIVE;TOP:-2PT;ADD_SUP:2PT;">
	(a)
</FONT>
</FONT>
</DT>
<DD STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
	Equity
	earnings from Northern Border is net of the 12-year amortization of a $10&nbsp;million transaction fee paid to the operator of Northern Border at
	the time of the Partnership's additional 20&nbsp;percent acquisition in April&nbsp;2006.
<BR>
<BR>
</FONT>
</DD>
<DT STYLE='FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;MARGIN-BOTTOM:-9PT;'>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:6PT;POSITION:RELATIVE;TOP:-2PT;ADD_SUP:2PT;">
	(b)
</FONT>
</FONT>
</DT>
<DD STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
	Equity
	Earnings represents our share in investee's earnings and does not include any impairment charge on the equity method investment recorded as a
	reduction of carrying value of these investments.
<BR>
<BR>
</FONT>
</DD>
<DT STYLE='FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;MARGIN-BOTTOM:-9PT;'>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:6PT;POSITION:RELATIVE;TOP:-2PT;ADD_SUP:2PT;">
	(c)
</FONT>
</FONT>
</DT>
<DD STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
	During
	the fourth quarter of 2015, we recognized an impairment charge on our investment in Great Lakes amounting to $199&nbsp;million. See discussion
	below.
</FONT>
</DD>
</DL>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
<B>
<!-- COMMAND=ADD_TXTHEX,"PMS287" -->
</B>
</FONT>
<FONT COLOR="#0C2E82" SIZE=1>
<B>
	Northern Border
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
	The Partnership owns a 50&nbsp;percent general partner interest in Northern Border. The other 50&nbsp;percent partnership interest in Northern Border is held by ONEOK
	Partners,&nbsp;L.P., a publicly traded limited partnership.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
	TC&nbsp;PipeLines
	Intermediate Limited Partnership, as one of the general partners, may be exposed to the commitments and contingencies of Northern Border. The Partnership
	holds a 98.9899&nbsp;percent limited partnership interest in TC&nbsp;PipeLines Intermediate Limited Partnership.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
	Northern
	Border has a FERC-approved settlement agreement which established maximum long-term transportation rates and charges on the Northern Border system effective
	January&nbsp;1, 2013. Northern Border is required to file for new rates no later than January&nbsp;1,&nbsp;2018.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
	The
	Partnership recorded no undistributed earnings from Northern Border for the years ended December&nbsp;31, 2015, 2014 and&nbsp;2013.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
	At
	December&nbsp;31, 2015 and 2014, the Partnership had a $117&nbsp;million difference between the carrying value of Northern Border and the underlying equity in the net
	assets primarily resulting from the recognition and inclusion of goodwill in the Partnership's investment in Northern Border relating to the Partnership's April&nbsp;2006 acquisition of an
	additional 20&nbsp;percent general partnership interest in Northern Border. As of December&nbsp;31, 2015, no impairment has been identified in our investment in Northern Border.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
	The
	summarized financial information for Northern Border is as follows:
</FONT>
</P>

<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
<B>
<!-- COMMAND=ADD_TXTHEX,"PMS287" -->
</B>
</FONT>
<FONT COLOR="#0C2E82" SIZE=1>
<B>
	Great Lakes
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
	The Partnership owns a 46.45&nbsp;percent general partner interest in Great Lakes. TransCanada owns the other 53.55&nbsp;percent partnership interest. TC GL Intermediate
	Limited Partnership, as one of the general partners, may be exposed to the commitments and contingencies of Great Lakes. The Partnership holds a 98.9899&nbsp;percent limited partnership interest in
	TC GL Intermediate Limited Partnership.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
	On
	November&nbsp;14, 2013, FERC approved a settlement between Great Lakes and its customers to modify its transportation rates effective November&nbsp;1, 2013. The
	settlement increases maximum recourse transportation rates by approximately 21&nbsp;percent. The settlement also requires that Great Lakes file for new rates to be in effect no later than
	January&nbsp;1,&nbsp;2018.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
	The
	Partnership recorded no undistributed earnings from Great Lakes for the years ended December&nbsp;31, 2015, 2014, and&nbsp;2013.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
	The
	Partnership made equity contributions to Great Lakes of $4&nbsp;million and $5&nbsp;million in the first and fourth quarter of 2015, respectively. These amounts
	represent the Partnership's 46.45&nbsp;percent share of a $9&nbsp;million and $10&nbsp;million cash call from Great Lakes to make scheduled debt repayments.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
	Despite
	the recent improvement in income from our investment in Great Lakes since 2013, including favorable current year results, its long-term value has been adversely
	impacted by the changing natural gas flows in its market region as well as our conclusion in the fourth quarter that other strategic alternatives to increase its utilization or revenue were no longer
	feasible. As a result, we determined that the carrying value of our investment in Great Lakes was in excess of its fair value and that the decline is not temporary. Accordingly, we concluded that the
	carrying value of our investment in Great Lakes was&nbsp;impaired.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
	Our
	analysis determined that the fair value of our investment in Great Lakes is $465&nbsp;million, resulting in an impairment charge of $199&nbsp;million in the fourth
	quarter of 2015, reflected as Impairment of equity-method investment on our Statement of Income for the year ended December&nbsp;31, 2015. The impairment charge reduced the difference between the
	carrying value of our investment in Great Lakes and the underlying equity in the net assets, which was reduced to $260&nbsp;million at December&nbsp;31, 2015
	(2014&nbsp;&#150;&nbsp;$458&nbsp;million) and represents the equity method goodwill remaining in our investment in Great Lakes relating to the Partnership's
	February&nbsp;2007 acquisition of a 46.45&nbsp;percent general partner interest in Great&nbsp;Lakes.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
	Our
	assumptions related to the estimated fair value of our remaining equity investment in Great Lakes could be negatively impacted by near and long-term conditions
	including:
</FONT>
</P>
<DL COMPACT>
<DT STYLE='FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;MARGIN-BOTTOM:-9PT;'>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
	&#149;
</FONT>
</DT>
<DD STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
	future
	regulatory rate action or settlement,
<BR>
<BR>
</FONT>
</DD>
<DT STYLE='FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;MARGIN-BOTTOM:-9PT;'>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
	&#149;
</FONT>
</DT>
<DD STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
	valuation
	of Great lakes in future transactions,
<BR>
<BR>
</FONT>
</DD>
<DT STYLE='FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;MARGIN-BOTTOM:-9PT;'>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
	&#149;
</FONT>
</DT>
<DD STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
	changes
	in customer demand at Great Lakes for pipeline capacity and services,
<BR>
<BR>
</FONT>
</DD>
<DT STYLE='FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;MARGIN-BOTTOM:-9PT;'>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
	&#149;
</FONT>
</DT>
<DD STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
	changes
	in North American natural gas production in the major producing basins,
<BR>
<BR>
</FONT>
</DD>
<DT STYLE='FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;MARGIN-BOTTOM:-9PT;'>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
	&#149;
</FONT>
</DT>
<DD STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
	changes
	in natural gas prices and natural gas storage market conditions, and
<BR>
<BR>
</FONT>
</DD>
<DT STYLE='FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;MARGIN-BOTTOM:-9PT;'>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
	&#149;
</FONT>
</DT>
<DD STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
	changes
	in other long-term strategic objectives.
</FONT>
</DD>
</DL>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
	There
	is a risk that adverse changes in these key assumptions could result in additional future impairment of the carrying value of our investment in Great&nbsp;Lakes.
</FONT>
</P>

<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
<B>
<!-- COMMAND=ADD_TXTHEX,"PMS287" -->
</B>
</FONT>
<FONT COLOR="#0C2E82" SIZE=1>
<B>
	NOTE 6&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;ACQUISITIONS
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
<B>
<!-- COMMAND=ADD_TXTHEX,"PMS287" -->
</B>
</FONT>
<FONT COLOR="#0C2E82" SIZE=1>
<B>
	2015 GTN Acquisition
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
	On April&nbsp;1, 2015, the Partnership acquired the remaining 30&nbsp;percent interest in GTN from a subsidiary of TransCanada (2015 GTN Acquisition), which resulted in
	GTN being wholly-owned by the Partnership. The total purchase price of the 2015 GTN Acquisition was $446&nbsp;million plus the final purchase price adjustment of $11&nbsp;million, for a total
	of $457&nbsp;million. The purchase price consisted of $264&nbsp;million in cash (including the final purchase price adjustment of $11&nbsp;million), the assumption of $98&nbsp;million in
	proportional GTN debt and the issuance of 1,900,000&nbsp;new Class&nbsp;B units to TransCanada valued at $50 each, representing a limited partner interest in the Partnership with a total value
	of $95&nbsp;million.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
	The
	Partnership funded the cash portion of the transaction using a portion of the proceeds received on our March&nbsp;13, 2015 debt offering (refer to Note&nbsp;7).
	The Class&nbsp;B units entitle TransCanada to a distribution based on 30&nbsp;percent of GTN's annual distributions as follows: (i)&nbsp;100&nbsp;percent of distributions above
	$20&nbsp;million through March&nbsp;31, 2020; and (ii)&nbsp;25&nbsp;percent of distributions above $20&nbsp;million thereafter. Under the terms of the Partnership Agreement, the
	Class&nbsp;B distribution will be initially calculated to equal 30&nbsp;percent of GTN's distributable cash flow for the nine months ended December&nbsp;31, 2015, less $15&nbsp;million.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
	Prior
	to this transaction, the remaining 30&nbsp;percent interest held by a subsidiary of TransCanada was reflected as a non-controlling interest in the Partnership's
	consolidated financial statements. The 2015 GTN Acquisition of this already-consolidated entity was accounted as a
</FONT>
</P>
<P ALIGN="RIGHT" STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">

<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">

	transaction
	between entities under common control, similar to a pooling of interests, whereby the acquired interest was recorded at TransCanada's carrying value and the total excess purchase price
	paid was recorded as a reduction in Partners' Equity.

<DL COMPACT>
<DT STYLE='FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;MARGIN-BOTTOM:-9PT;'>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">

</FONT>

<DD STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
	Total
	purchase price of $457&nbsp;million less the assumption of $98&nbsp;million of proportional GTN debt by the Partnership.
<BR>
<BR>
</FONT>
</DD>
<DT STYLE='FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;MARGIN-BOTTOM:-9PT;'>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:6PT;POSITION:RELATIVE;TOP:-2PT;ADD_SUP:2PT;">

</FONT>

<DD STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
	The
	excess purchase price of $127&nbsp;million was recorded as a reduction in Partners' Equity.
</FONT>
</DD>
</DL>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
	Our
	General Partner also contributed approximately $2&nbsp;million to maintain its effective two percent interest in the Partnership.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
<B>
<!-- COMMAND=ADD_TXTHEX,"PMS287" -->
</B>
</FONT>
<FONT COLOR="#0C2E82" SIZE=1>
<B>
	2014 Bison Acquisition
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
	On October&nbsp;1, 2014, the Partnership acquired the remaining 30&nbsp;percent interest in Bison from a subsidiary of TransCanada. The total purchase price of the 2014
	Bison Acquisition was $215&nbsp;million plus purchase price adjustments of $2&nbsp;million. The acquisition of Bison was financed through combinations of (i)&nbsp;net proceeds from the ATM
	Program (refer to Note&nbsp;9), and (ii)&nbsp;short-term financing (refer to Note&nbsp;7).
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
	Prior
	to this transaction, the remaining 30&nbsp;percent interest held by a subsidiary of TransCanada was reflected as non-controlling interest in the Partnership's
	consolidated financial statements. The 2014 Bison Acquisition of this already-consolidated entity was accounted as a transaction between entities under common control, similar to a pooling of
	interests, whereby the acquired interest was recorded at TransCanada's carrying value and the total excess purchase price paid was recorded as a reduction in Partners' Equity.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">

	purchase price was allocated as follows:

<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
	The
	excess purchase price of $29&nbsp;million was recorded as a reduction in Partners' Equity.
</FONT>
</P>
</EFX_UNIDENTIFIED_TABLE>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
<B>
<!-- COMMAND=ADD_TXTHEX,"PMS287" -->
</B>
</FONT>
<FONT COLOR="#0C2E82" SIZE=1>
<B>
	2013 Acquisition
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
	On July&nbsp;1, 2013, the Partnership acquired a 45&nbsp;percent membership interest in each of GTN and Bison from subsidiaries of TransCanada, increasing the
	Partnership's ownership in each GTN and Bison to 70&nbsp;percent. The total purchase price of the 2013 Acquisition was $1,050&nbsp;million plus purchase price adjustments. The purchase price
	consisted of (i)&nbsp;$750&nbsp;million for the GTN membership interest (less $146&nbsp;million, which reflected 45&nbsp;percent of GTN's outstanding debt at the time of the 2013
	Acquisition), (ii)&nbsp;$300&nbsp;million for the membership interest in Bison, (iii)&nbsp;$17&nbsp;million in working capital adjustments and (iv)&nbsp;Carty Lateral consideration of
	$25&nbsp;million (see&nbsp;below).
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
	The
	resulting $921&nbsp;million (after working capital adjustments) paid by the Partnership was financed through a combination of (i)&nbsp;a public offering of
	8,855,000&nbsp;common units at $43.85 per common unit resulting in net proceeds of $373&nbsp;million (refer to Note&nbsp;9), (ii)&nbsp;borrowing of $500&nbsp;million in term loans (refer
	to Note&nbsp;7), (iii)&nbsp;a capital contribution from the General Partner of $8&nbsp;million which was required to maintain the General Partner's effective two percent general partner
	interest in the Partnership (refer to Note&nbsp;9), and (iv)&nbsp;a draw on the Partnership's existing $500&nbsp;million Senior Credit Facility and (v)&nbsp;cash on&nbsp;hand.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
	Pursuant
	to the acquisition agreement between the Partnership and TransCanada relating to the Partnership's acquisition of an additional 45&nbsp;percent membership
	interest in GTN, the Partnership agreed to make an additional payment of $25&nbsp;million to TransCanada if Portland General Electric Company executed a firm transportation service agreement by
	December&nbsp;31, 2014 containing agreed terms and relating to transportation on GTN's Carty Lateral. On December&nbsp;11, 2013, Portland General Electric Company executed this firm
	transportation service agreement and as a result, the Partnership paid an additional $25&nbsp;million on April&nbsp;11,&nbsp;2014.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
<B>
<!-- COMMAND=ADD_TXTHEX,"PMS287" -->
</B>
</FONT>
<FONT COLOR="#0C2E82" SIZE=1>
<B>
	F-15
</B>
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;TC
	PIPELINES, LP
</FONT>
</P>

	The
	2013 Acquisition was accounted for as a transaction between entities under common control, similar to a pooling of interests, whereby the assets and liabilities of
	GTN and Bison were recorded at TransCanada's carrying value and the Partnership's historical financial information, except net income per common unit, was recast to consolidate GTN and Bison for
	all periods presented.
</FONT>
</P>

<!-- END OF USER-SPECIFIED TAGGED TABLE -->
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
	As
	the fair market value for the additional 45&nbsp;percent interests in each of GTN and Bison was greater than the acquired net assets of GTN and Bison by
	$262&nbsp;million and $12&nbsp;million, respectively, the total excess purchase price of $274&nbsp;million was recorded as a reduction in Partners' Equity, including the Carty Lateral
	consideration. The retrospective consolidation of GTN and Bison increased net income attributable to controlling interests by $26&nbsp;million for the year ended December&nbsp;31, 2013.
	However, this amount was excluded from equity attributable to controlling interests and the historical net income per common unit was not adjusted as the pre-acquisition earnings was allocated to
	TransCanada (refer to Note&nbsp;12).
</FONT>
</P>

<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
	The
	Partnership's Senior Credit Facility consists of a $500&nbsp;million senior revolving credit facility with a banking syndicate, maturing November&nbsp;20, 2017,
	under which $200&nbsp;million was outstanding at December&nbsp;31, 2015 (2014&nbsp;&#150;&nbsp;$330&nbsp;million), leaving $300&nbsp;million available for future
	borrowing.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
	At
	the Partnership's option, the interest rate on the outstanding borrowings under the Senior Credit Facility may be lenders' base rate or the London Interbank Offered
	Rate (LIBOR) plus, in either case, an applicable margin that is based on the Partnership's long-term unsecured credit ratings. The Senior Credit Facility permits the Partnership to specify the
	portion of the borrowings to be covered by specific interest rate options and, for LIBOR-based borrowings, to specify the interest rate period. The Partnership is required to pay a commitment fee
	based on its credit rating and on the unused principal amount of the commitments under the Senior Credit Facility. The Senior Credit Facility has a feature
</FONT>
</P>
<P ALIGN="RIGHT" STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
<B>
<!-- COMMAND=ADD_TXTHEX,"PMS287" -->
</B>
</FONT>
<FONT COLOR="#0C2E82" SIZE=1>
<B>
	F-16
</B>
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;2015
	ANNUAL REPORT
</FONT>
</P>
<HR NOSHADE>
<P STYLE='FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE:ALWAYS'>
</P>
<!-- ZEQ.=3,SEQ=97,EFW="2227406",CP="TC PIPELINES, LP",DN="1",CHK=963531,FOLIO='F-16',FILE='DISK132:[15ZCW1.15ZCW77001]FI77001A.;44',USER='IMORTON',CD='24-FEB-2016;14:42' -->
<A NAME="A2227406Z10-K_HTM_PAGE_FI77001_1_17">
</A>
<BR>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
	whereby
	at any time, so long as no event of default has occurred and is continuing, the Partnership may request an increase in the Senior Credit Facility of up to $250&nbsp;million, but no
	lender has an obligation to increase their respective share of the&nbsp;facility.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
	The
	LIBOR-based interest rate on the Senior Credit Facility averaged 1.44&nbsp;percent for the year ended December&nbsp;31, 2015
	(2014&nbsp;&#150;&nbsp;1.41&nbsp;percent; 2013&nbsp;&#150;&nbsp;1.44&nbsp;percent). The interest rate was 1.50&nbsp;percent at
	December&nbsp;31, 2015 (December&nbsp;31, 2014&nbsp;&#150;&nbsp;1.41&nbsp;percent).
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
	On
	July&nbsp;1, 2013, the Partnership entered into a term loan agreement with a syndicate of lenders for a $500&nbsp;million term loan credit facility (2013 Term
	Loan Facility). On July&nbsp;2, 2013, the Partnership borrowed $500&nbsp;million under the 2013 Term Loan Facility, to pay a portion of the purchase price of the 2013 Acquisition, maturing on
	July&nbsp;1, 2018. The 2013 Term Loan Facility bears interest based, at the Partnership's election, on the LIBOR or the base rate plus, in either case, an applicable margin. The base rate equals
	the highest of (i)&nbsp;SunTrust Bank's prime rate, (ii)&nbsp;0.50&nbsp;percent above the federal funds rate and (iii)&nbsp;1.00&nbsp;percent above one-month LIBOR. The applicable margin
	for the term loan is based on the Partnership's senior debt rating and ranges between 1.125&nbsp;percent and 2.000&nbsp;percent for LIBOR borrowings and 0.125&nbsp;percent and
	1.000&nbsp;percent for base rate borrowings.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
	The
	LIBOR-based interest rate on the 2013 Term Loan Facility averaged 1.44&nbsp;percent for the year ended December&nbsp;31, 2015
	(2014&nbsp;&#150;&nbsp;1.41&nbsp;percent). After hedging activity, the interest rate incurred on the Term Loan Facility averaged 1.85&nbsp;percent for the year ended
	December&nbsp;31, 2015 (2014&nbsp;&#150;&nbsp;1.82&nbsp;percent). Prior to hedging activities, the LIBOR-based interest rate was 1.50&nbsp;percent at
	December&nbsp;31, 2015 (December&nbsp;31, 2014&nbsp;&#150;&nbsp;1.41&nbsp;percent).
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
	On
	September&nbsp;30, 2015, the Partnership entered into an agreement for a $170&nbsp;million term loan credit facility (2015 Term Loan Facility). The Partnership
	borrowed $170&nbsp;million under the 2015 Term Loan Facility to refinance its Short-Term Loan Facility which matured on September&nbsp;30, 2015. The 2015 Term Loan Facility matures on
	October&nbsp;1, 2018. The LIBOR-based interest rate on the 2015 Term Loan Facility averaged 1.47&nbsp;percent for the year ended December&nbsp;31, 2015. The interest rate was
	1.39&nbsp;percent at December&nbsp;31,&nbsp;2015.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
	The
	2013 Term Loan Facility and the 2015 Term Loan Facility (Term Loan Facilities) and the Senior Credit Facility require the Partnership to maintain a certain leverage
	ratio (debt to adjusted cash flow [net income plus cash distributions received, extraordinary losses, interest expense, expense for taxes paid or accrued, and depreciation and
	amortization expense less equity earnings and extraordinary gains]). In the quarter in which an acquisition has occurred, and the two quarters following the acquisition, the allowable
	leverage ratio increases to 5.50&nbsp;to&nbsp;1.00. Thereafter, the ratio returns to 5.00&nbsp;to&nbsp;1.00. The allowable ratio for the quarter ended December&nbsp;31, 2015 is
	5.50&nbsp;to&nbsp;1.00. The leverage ratio was 4.68 to 1.00&nbsp;as of December&nbsp;31, 2015. The Senior Credit Facility and the Term Loan Facilities contain additional covenants that
	include restrictions on entering into mergers, consolidations and sales of assets, granting liens, material amendments to the Partnership Agreement, incurrence of additional debt by the
	Partnership's subsidiaries and distributions to unitholders. Upon any breach of these covenants, amounts outstanding under the Senior Credit Facility and the Term Loan Facilities may become
	immediately due and&nbsp;payable.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
	On
	March&nbsp;13, 2015, the Partnership closed a $350&nbsp;million public offering of senior unsecured notes bearing an interest rate of 4.375&nbsp;percent
	maturing March&nbsp;13, 2025. The net proceeds of $346&nbsp;million were used to fund a portion of the acquisition of the remaining 30&nbsp;percent interest in GTN (refer to Note&nbsp;6)
	and&nbsp;to reduce the amount outstanding under our Senior Credit Facility. The indenture for the notes contains customary investment grade covenants.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
	On
	June&nbsp;1, 2015, GTN's 5.09&nbsp;percent unsecured Senior Notes matured. Also, on June&nbsp;1, 2015, GTN entered into a $75&nbsp;million unsecured variable
	rate term loan facility (Unsecured Term Loan Facility), which requires yearly principal payments until its maturity on June&nbsp;1, 2019. The variable interest is based on LIBOR plus an
	applicable margin. The LIBOR-based interest rate on the Unsecured Term Loan Facility for the year ended December&nbsp;31, 2015 averaged 1.16&nbsp;percent and was 1.15&nbsp;percent at
	December&nbsp;31, 2015. GTN's Unsecured Senior Notes, along with this new Unsecured Term Loan Facility contain a covenant that limits total debt to no greater than 70&nbsp;percent of GTN's
	total capitalization. GTN's total debt to total capitalization ratio at December&nbsp;31, 2015 is 43.8&nbsp;percent.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
	The
	Series&nbsp;D Senior Notes, which require yearly principal payments until its maturity, are secured by Tuscarora's transportation contracts, supporting agreements
	and substantially all of Tuscarora's property. The note purchase agreements contain certain provisions that include, among other items, limitations on additional indebtedness and distributions
	to&nbsp;partners.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
	At
	December&nbsp;31, 2015, the Partnership was in compliance with its financial covenants, in addition to the other covenants which include restrictions on entering
	into mergers, consolidations and sales of assets, granting liens, material amendments to the second amended and restated agreement of limited partnership (Partnership Agreement), incurring
	additional debt and distributions to&nbsp;unitholders.
</FONT>
</P>

<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
	The
	Partnership collects estimated future removal costs related to its transmission and gathering facilities in its current rates and recognizes regulatory liabilities
	in this respect in the balance sheet. Estimated costs associated with the future removal of transmission and gathering facilities are collected through depreciation as allowed by FERC. These
	amounts do not represent asset retirement obligations as defined by FASB ASC 410,
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
<I>
	Accounting for Asset Retirement Obligations
</I>
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
	.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
<B>
<!-- COMMAND=ADD_TXTHEX,"PMS287" -->
</B>
</FONT>
<FONT COLOR="#0C2E82" SIZE=1>
<B>
	NOTE 9&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;PARTNERS' EQUITY
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
	At December&nbsp;31, 2015, the Partnership had 64,317,449&nbsp;common units outstanding, of which 47,232,618&nbsp;were held by non-affiliates and
	17,084,831&nbsp;common units were held by subsidiaries of TransCanada, including 5,797,106&nbsp;common units held by our General Partner. Additionally, TransCanada, through our General
	Partner, owns 100&nbsp;percent of our IDRs and an effective two percent general partner interest in the Partnership. TransCanada also holds 100&nbsp;percent of our 1,900,000&nbsp;outstanding
	Class&nbsp;B&nbsp;units.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
<B>
<!-- COMMAND=ADD_TXTHEX,"PMS287" -->
</B>
</FONT>
<FONT COLOR="#0C2E82" SIZE=1>
<B>
	ATM Equity Issuance Program (ATM&nbsp;Program)
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
	In August&nbsp;2014, the Partnership entered into an Equity Distribution Agreement (the&nbsp;EDA) with five different financial institutions (Managers), pursuant to
	which, the Partnership may from time to time, offer and sell common units having an aggregate offering price of up to $200&nbsp;million. Sales of such common units will be made by means of
	ordinary brokers' transactions on the NYSE at market prices, in block transactions or as otherwise agreed upon by one or more of the Managers and the Partnership.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
	In
	2015, the Partnership issued 0.7&nbsp;million common units under the ATM Program generating net proceeds of approximately $43&nbsp;million, plus an additional
	$1&nbsp;million from the General Partner's to maintain its effective two percent interest. The commissions to our sales agents were approximately $0.4&nbsp;million. The net proceeds were used
	for general partnership purposes.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
	In
	2014, the Partnership issued 1.3&nbsp;million common units under the ATM Program generating net proceeds of approximately $71&nbsp;million, plus an additional
	$2&nbsp;million from the General Partner's to maintain its effective two percent interest. The commissions to our sales agents were approximately $1&nbsp;million. The net proceeds were used to
	finance the 2014 Bison Acquisition (refer to Note&nbsp;6).
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
<B>
<!-- COMMAND=ADD_TXTHEX,"PMS287" -->
</B>
</FONT>
<FONT COLOR="#0C2E82" SIZE=1>
<B>
	Issuance of Class&nbsp;B units
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
	On April&nbsp;1, 2015, we issued Class&nbsp;B units to TransCanada to finance a portion of the 2015 GTN Acquisition. The Class&nbsp;B units entitle TransCanada to an
	annual distribution which is an amount based on 30&nbsp;percent of cash distributions from GTN above certain annual thresholds (refer to Note&nbsp;6). The Class&nbsp;B units contain no
	mandatory or optional redemption features and are also non-convertible, non-exchangeable, non-voting and rank equally with common units upon liquidation.
</FONT>
</P>
<P ALIGN="RIGHT" STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
<B>
<!-- COMMAND=ADD_TXTHEX,"PMS287" -->
</B>
</FONT>
<FONT COLOR="#0C2E82" SIZE=1>
<B>
	F-18
</B>
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;2015
	ANNUAL REPORT
</FONT>
</P>
<HR NOSHADE>
<P STYLE='FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE:ALWAYS'>
</P>
<!-- ZEQ.=5,SEQ=99,EFW="2227406",CP="TC PIPELINES, LP",DN="1",CHK=614164,FOLIO='F-18',FILE='DISK132:[15ZCW1.15ZCW77001]FI77001A.;44',USER='IMORTON',CD='24-FEB-2016;14:42' -->
<A NAME="A2227406Z10-K_HTM_PAGE_FI77001_1_19">
</A>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
	The
	Class&nbsp;B units' equity account will be increased by the excess of 30&nbsp;percent of GTN's distributions over the annual threshold until such amount is
	declared for distribution and paid in the first quarter beginning 2016 and annually thereafter.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
<B>
<!-- COMMAND=ADD_TXTHEX,"PMS287" -->
</B>
</FONT>
<FONT COLOR="#0C2E82" SIZE=1>
<B>
	Equity issuance in connection with the 2013 Acquisition
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
	On May&nbsp;22, 2013, the Partnership closed a public offering of 8,855,000&nbsp;common units, including 1,155,000&nbsp;common units purchased pursuant to the exercise
	of the underwriters' option to purchase additional common units, at a price to the public of $43.85 per common unit for gross proceeds of $388&nbsp;million and net proceeds of
	$373&nbsp;million after unit issuance costs. The General Partner maintained its
	effective two percent general partner interest in the Partnership by contributing $8&nbsp;million to the Partnership in connection with the offering. (Refer to Note&nbsp;6).
</FONT>
</P>

<DL COMPACT>
<DT STYLE='FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;MARGIN-BOTTOM:-9PT;'>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:6PT;POSITION:RELATIVE;TOP:-2PT;ADD_SUP:2PT;">
	(a)
</FONT>

	Recast
	as discussed in Note&nbsp;2 and Note&nbsp;6.
</FONT>
