</EFX_UNIDENTIFIED_TABLE>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
<B>
<!-- COMMAND=ADD_TXTHEX,"PMS287" -->
</B>
</FONT>
<FONT COLOR="#0C2E82" SIZE=1>
<B>
	NOTE 12&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;NET INCOME (LOSS) PER COMMON UNIT
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
	Net income (loss) per common unit is computed by dividing net income attributable to controlling interests, after deduction of amounts attributable to the General Partner
	and to TransCanada and its subsidiaries, by the weighted average number of common units outstanding.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
	The
	amounts allocable to the General Partner equals an amount based upon the General Partner's effective two percent general partner interest, plus an amount equal to
	incentive distributions. Incentive distributions are paid to the General Partner if quarterly cash distributions on the common units exceed levels specified in the Partnership Agreement (refer to
	Note&nbsp;13).
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
	The
	amounts allocable to TransCanada and its subsidiaries represents amount allocable to the Class&nbsp;B units (refer to Note&nbsp;6-2015 GTN Acquisition) and
	amounts allocable to GTN and Bison's former parent as a result of recast (refer to Note&nbsp;6- 2013 Acquisition).
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
	The
	amount allocable to GTN and Bison's former parent represents income of GTN and Bison prior to the 2013 Acquisition.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
	The
	amount allocable to the Class&nbsp;B units in 2015 equals an amount based upon 30&nbsp;percent of GTN's distributable cash flow during the nine months ended
	December&nbsp;31, 2015 less $15&nbsp;million.
</FONT>
</P>
<EFX_UNIDENTIFIED_TABLE>
<A NAME="FIS_UNIDENTIFIED_TABLE_35"></A>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
<B>
<!-- COMMAND=ADD_TXTHEX,"PMS287" -->
</B>
</FONT>
<FONT COLOR="#0C2E82" SIZE=1>
<B>
	F-19
</B>
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;TC
	PIPELINES, LP
</FONT>
</P>

<!-- ZEQ.=6,SEQ=100,EFW="2227406",CP="TC PIPELINES, LP",DN="1",CHK=306223,FOLIO='F-19',FILE='DISK132:[15ZCW1.15ZCW77001]FI77001A.;44',USER='IMORTON',CD='24-FEB-2016;14:42' -->
<A NAME="A2227406Z10-K_HTM_PAGE_FI77001_1_20">
</A>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
	Net
	income (loss) per common unit was determined as follows:
</FONT>
</P>
<!-- USER-SPECIFIED TAGGED TABLE -->

<DT STYLE='FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;MARGIN-BOTTOM:-9PT;'>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:6PT;POSITION:RELATIVE;TOP:-2PT;ADD_SUP:2PT;">
	(b)
</FONT>
</FONT>
</DT>
<DD STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
	Net
	income allocable to General and Limited Partners excludes net income attributed to GTN's and Bison's former parent as it was allocated to
	TransCanada and was not allocable to either the general partner, common units or Class&nbsp;B units (refer to Note&nbsp;6&nbsp;&#150;&nbsp;2013 Acquisition).
<BR>
<BR>
</FONT>
</DD>
<DT STYLE='FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;MARGIN-BOTTOM:-9PT;'>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:6PT;POSITION:RELATIVE;TOP:-2PT;ADD_SUP:2PT;">
	(c)
</FONT>
</FONT>
</DT>
<DD STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
	Net
	income allocable to General and Limited Partners is allocated based on their respective participation rights, after giving effect to any priority
	income allocation for incentive distributions that are allocated 100&nbsp;percent to the General Partner. Under the terms of the Partnership Agreement, for any quarterly period, the
	participation of the IDRs is limited to the available cash distributions declared. Accordingly, incentive distributions allocated to the General Partner was based from the Partnership's available
	cash during the current reporting period, but declared and paid in the subsequent reporting period.
<BR>
<BR>
</FONT>
</DD>
<DT STYLE='FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;MARGIN-BOTTOM:-9PT;'>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:6PT;POSITION:RELATIVE;TOP:-2PT;ADD_SUP:2PT;">
	(d)
</FONT>
</FONT>
</DT>
<DD STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
	As
	discussed in Notes&nbsp;6 and&nbsp;9, the Class&nbsp;B units entitle TransCanada to a distribution which is an amount based on
	30&nbsp;percent of GTN's distributions after achieving certain annual thresholds. The distribution will be payable in the first quarter with respect to the prior year's distributions. Consistent
	with the application of Accounting Standards Codification (ASC) Topic 260&nbsp;&#150;&nbsp;"Earnings per share," the Partnership allocated a portion of net income
	attributable to controlling interests to the Class&nbsp;B units upon 30&nbsp;percent of GTN's total distributable cash flows exceeding $15&nbsp;million for the nine month period ended
	December&nbsp;31, 2015. During the nine months ended December&nbsp;31, 2015, 30&nbsp;percent of GTN's total distributable cash flow was $27&nbsp;million. As a result, $12&nbsp;million of
	net income attributable to controlling interests was allocated to the Class&nbsp;B units in 2015. On February&nbsp;12, 2016, this amount was paid to TransCanada (Refer to Note&nbsp;13
	and&nbsp;22).
</FONT>
</DD>
</DL>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
<B>
<!-- COMMAND=ADD_TXTHEX,"PMS287" -->
</B>
</FONT>
<FONT COLOR="#0C2E82" SIZE=1>
<B>
	NOTE 13&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;CASH DISTRIBUTIONS
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
	The Partnership makes cash distributions to its partners with respect to each calendar quarter within 45&nbsp;days after the end of each quarter. Distributions are based
	on Available Cash, as defined in the Partnership Agreement, which includes all cash and cash equivalents of the Partnership and working capital borrowings less reserves established by the General
	Partner.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
	Pursuant
	to the Partnership Agreement, the General Partner receives two percent of all cash distributions in regard to its general partner interest and is also entitled
	to incentive distributions as described below. The unitholders receive the remaining portion of the cash distribution.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
	The
	following table illustrates the percentage allocations of available cash from operating surplus between the common unitholders and our General Partner based on the
	specified target distribution levels. The percentage interests set forth below for our General Partner include its two percent general partner interest and IDRs, and assume our General Partner has
	contributed any additional capital necessary to maintain its two percent general partner interest. The distribution to the General Partner illustrated below, other than in its capacity as a holder
	of 5,797,106&nbsp;common units that are in excess of its effective two percent general partner interest, represents the&nbsp;IDRs.
</FONT>
</P>

<DL COMPACT>
<DT STYLE='FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;MARGIN-BOTTOM:-9PT;'>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:6PT;POSITION:RELATIVE;TOP:-2PT;ADD_SUP:2PT;">
	(a)
</FONT>
</FONT>
</DT>
<DD STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
	The
	distributions paid for the year ended December&nbsp;31, 2015 included incentive distributions to the General Partner of $2&nbsp;million
	(2014&nbsp;&#150;&nbsp;$1&nbsp;million). There were no incentive distributions paid to the General Partner in the year ended December&nbsp;31,&nbsp;2013.
<BR>
<BR>
</FONT>
</DD>
<DT STYLE='FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;MARGIN-BOTTOM:-9PT;'>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:6PT;POSITION:RELATIVE;TOP:-2PT;ADD_SUP:2PT;">
	(b)
</FONT>
</FONT>
</DT>
<DD STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
	On
	February&nbsp;12, 2016, we paid a cash distribution of $0.89 per unit on our outstanding common units to unitholders of record at the close of
	business on February&nbsp;2, 2016 (refer to Note&nbsp;22).
<BR>
<BR>
</FONT>
</DD>
<DT STYLE='FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;MARGIN-BOTTOM:-9PT;'>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:6PT;POSITION:RELATIVE;TOP:-2PT;ADD_SUP:2PT;">
	(c)
</FONT>
</FONT>
</DT>
<DD STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
	The
	Class&nbsp;B units issued by us on April&nbsp;1, 2015 represent limited partner interests in us and entitle TransCanada to an annual
	distribution which is an amount based on 30&nbsp;percent of GTN's annual distributions after achieving certain annual thresholds (refer to Note&nbsp;6 and&nbsp;9).
<BR>
<BR>
</FONT>
</DD>
<DT STYLE='FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;MARGIN-BOTTOM:-9PT;'>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:6PT;POSITION:RELATIVE;TOP:-2PT;ADD_SUP:2PT;">
	(d)
</FONT>
</FONT>
</DT>
<DD STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
	On
	February&nbsp;12, 2016, we paid TransCanada $12&nbsp;million representing 30&nbsp;percent of GTN's total distributable cash flows for the nine
	months ended December&nbsp;31, 2015 less $15&nbsp;million (refer to Note&nbsp;9 and&nbsp;22).
</FONT>
</DD>
</DL>

<!-- ZEQ.=8,SEQ=102,EFW="2227406",CP="TC PIPELINES, LP",DN="1",CHK=316349,FOLIO='F-21',FILE='DISK132:[15ZCW1.15ZCW77001]FI77001A.;44',USER='IMORTON',CD='24-FEB-2016;14:42' -->
<A NAME="A2227406Z10-K_HTM_PAGE_FI77001_1_22">
</A>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
	At
	December&nbsp;31, 2015, Anadarko and Pacific Gas owed the Partnership approximately $4&nbsp;million and $3&nbsp;million, respectively, which is greater than
	10&nbsp;percent of our Trade accounts receivable. At December&nbsp;31, 2014, Anadarko and Pacific Gas each owed the Partnership approximately $4&nbsp;million, which is greater than
	10&nbsp;percent of our Trade accounts receivable.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
<B>
<!-- COMMAND=ADD_TXTHEX,"PMS287" -->
</B>
</FONT>
<FONT COLOR="#0C2E82" SIZE=1>
<B>
	NOTE 16&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;RELATED PARTY TRANSACTIONS
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
	The Partnership does not have any employees. The management and operating functions are provided by the General Partner. The General Partner does not receive a management
	fee in connection with its management of the Partnership. The Partnership reimburses the General Partner for all costs of services provided, including the costs of employee, officer and director
	compensation and benefits, and all other expenses necessary or appropriate to the conduct of the business of, and allocable to, the Partnership. Such costs include (i)&nbsp;overhead costs (such
	as office space and equipment) and (ii)&nbsp;out-of-pocket expenses related to the provision of such services. The Partnership Agreement provides that the General Partner will determine the
	costs that are allocable to the Partnership in any reasonable manner determined by the General Partner in its sole discretion. Total costs charged to the Partnership by the General Partner were
	$3&nbsp;million for each of the years ended December&nbsp;31, 2015, 2014 and&nbsp;2013.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
	As
	operator, TransCanada's subsidiaries provide capital and operating services to GTN, Northern Border, Bison, Great Lakes, North Baja and Tuscarora (together, "our
	pipeline systems"). TransCanada's subsidiaries incur costs on behalf of our pipeline systems, including, but not limited to, employee salary and benefit costs, and property and liability insurance
	costs.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
	Capital
	and operating costs charged to our pipeline systems for the years ended December&nbsp;31, 2015, 2014 and 2013 by TransCanada's subsidiaries and amounts payable
	to TransCanada's subsidiaries at December&nbsp;31, 2015 and 2014 are summarized in the following tables:
</FONT>
</P>

<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
	Great
	Lakes' earns transportation revenues from TransCanada and its affiliates, some of which are provided at discounted rates and some at maximum recourse rates. Great
	Lakes earned $125&nbsp;million of transportation revenues under these contracts in 2015 (2014&nbsp;&#150;&nbsp;$71&nbsp;million;
	2013&nbsp;&#150;&nbsp;$68&nbsp;million). This amount represents 71&nbsp;percent of total revenues earned by Great Lakes in 2015
	(2014&nbsp;&#150;&nbsp;49&nbsp;percent; 2013&nbsp;&#150;&nbsp;55&nbsp;percent). Great Lakes also earned $2&nbsp;million in affiliated rental
	revenue in 2015 (2014&nbsp;&#150;&nbsp;$2&nbsp;million and 2013&nbsp;&#150;&nbsp;$1&nbsp;million).
</FONT>
</P>
<P ALIGN="RIGHT" STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
<B>
<!-- COMMAND=ADD_TXTHEX,"PMS287" -->
</B>
</FONT>
<FONT COLOR="#0C2E82" SIZE=1>
<B>
	F-22
</B>
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;2015
	ANNUAL REPORT
</FONT>
</P>
<HR NOSHADE>
<P STYLE='FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE:ALWAYS'>
</P>
<!-- ZEQ.=9,SEQ=103,EFW="2227406",CP="TC PIPELINES, LP",DN="1",CHK=859229,FOLIO='F-22',FILE='DISK132:[15ZCW1.15ZCW77001]FI77001A.;44',USER='IMORTON',CD='24-FEB-2016;14:42' -->
<A NAME="A2227406Z10-K_HTM_PAGE_FI77001_1_23">
</A>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
	Revenue
	from TransCanada and its affiliates of $59&nbsp;million is included in the Partnership's equity earnings from Great Lakes in 2015
	(2014&nbsp;&#150;&nbsp;$34&nbsp;million; 2013&nbsp;&#150;&nbsp;$32&nbsp;million). At December&nbsp;31, 2015, $17&nbsp;million was included in
	Great Lakes' receivables in regards to the transportation contracts with TransCanada and its affiliates (2014&nbsp;&#150;&nbsp;$15&nbsp;million).
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
	Effective
	November&nbsp;1, 2014, Great Lakes executed contracts with an affiliate, ANR Pipeline Company (ANR), to provide firm service in Michigan and Wisconsin. These
	contracts were at the maximum FERC authorized rate and were intended to replace historical contracts. On December&nbsp;3, 2014, the FERC accepted and suspended Great Lakes' tariff records to
	become effective May&nbsp;3, 2015, subject to refund. On February&nbsp;2, 2015, FERC issued an Order granting a rehearing and clarification request submitted by Great Lakes, which allowed
	additional time for FERC to consider Great Lakes' request. Following extensive discussions with numerous
	shippers and other stakeholders, on April&nbsp;20, 2015, ANR filed a settlement with FERC that included an agreement by ANR to pay Great Lakes the difference between the historical and maximum
	rates (ANR&nbsp;Settlement). Great Lakes provided service to ANR under multiple service agreements and rates through May&nbsp;3, 2015 when Great Lakes' tariff records became effective and
	subject to refund. Great Lakes deferred an approximate $9&nbsp;million of revenue related to services performed in 2014 and approximately $14&nbsp;million of additional revenue related to
	services performed through May&nbsp;3, 2015 under such agreements. On October&nbsp;15, 2015, FERC accepted and approved the ANR Settlement. As a result, Great Lakes recognized the deferred
	transportation revenue of approximately $23&nbsp;million in the fourth quarter of&nbsp;2015.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
	Bison's
	former parent, TransCanada, made an equity contribution to Bison of $18&nbsp;million in the second quarter of 2013. This amount represents the TransCanada's
	75&nbsp;percent share of a $24&nbsp;million cash call from Bison to repay inter-affiliate debt primarily related to pipeline construction costs, including reclamation and
	restoration&nbsp;work.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
	Effective
	October&nbsp;1, 2013, GTN and Bison participated in the Partnership's cash management program. Prior to this, GTN and Bison were part of TransCanada's cash
	management program. This program matches short-term cash surpluses and borrowing requirements of participating subsidiaries, thus minimizing total borrowing from outside sources. Funds advanced
	under the program are considered to be a loan, accruing interest and repayable on demand. GTN and Bison will receive interest on funds advanced to the Partnership at the rate of interest earned by
	the Partnership on its short-term cash investments and will pay interest on funds advanced from the Partnership based on the Partnership's short-term borrowing costs. At December&nbsp;31, 2015
	and 2014, GTN and Bison did not have any demand loan receivable from an affiliate or a demand loan payable to an&nbsp;affiliate.
</FONT>
</P>

<DT STYLE='FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;MARGIN-BOTTOM:-9PT;'>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:6PT;POSITION:RELATIVE;TOP:-2PT;ADD_SUP:2PT;">
	(a)
</FONT>
</FONT>
</DT>
<DD STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
	Equity
	Earnings represents our share in investee's earnings and does not include any impairment charge on equity method goodwill included as part of
	the carrying value of our investments in unconsolidated affiliates.
<BR>
<BR>
</FONT>
</DD>
<DT STYLE='FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;MARGIN-BOTTOM:-9PT;'>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:6PT;POSITION:RELATIVE;TOP:-2PT;ADD_SUP:2PT;">
	(b)
</FONT>
</FONT>
</DT>
<DD STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
	During
	the three months ended December&nbsp;31, 2015, we recognized an impairment charge on our investment in Great Lakes amounting to
	$199&nbsp;million. No impairment has been identified on our investment in Northern Border (Refer to Note&nbsp;4).
</FONT>

<!-- ZEQ.=10,SEQ=104,EFW="2227406",CP="TC PIPELINES, LP",DN="1",CHK=380336,FOLIO='F-23',FILE='DISK132:[15ZCW1.15ZCW77001]FI77001A.;44',USER='IMORTON',CD='24-FEB-2016;14:42' -->
<A NAME="A2227406Z10-K_HTM_PAGE_FI77001_1_24">
</A>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
<B>
<!-- COMMAND=ADD_TXTHEX,"PMS287" -->
</B>
</FONT>
<FONT COLOR="#0C2E82" SIZE=1>
<B>
	NOTE 18&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;FAIR VALUE MEASUREMENTS
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
<B>
<!-- COMMAND=ADD_TXTHEX,"PMS287" -->
</B>
</FONT>
<FONT COLOR="#0C2E82" SIZE=1>
<B>
	(a)&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Fair Value Hierarchy
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
	Under ASC 820, Fair Value Measurements and Disclosures, fair value measurements are characterized in one of three levels based upon the input used to arrive at the
	measurement. The three levels of the fair value hierarchy are as&nbsp;follows:
</FONT>
</P>
<DL COMPACT>
<DT STYLE='FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;MARGIN-BOTTOM:-9PT;'>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
	&#149;
</FONT>
</DT>
<DD STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
	Level&nbsp;1
	inputs are quoted prices (unadjusted) in active markets for identical assets or liabilities that we have the ability to access at the
	measurement&nbsp;date.
<BR>
<BR>
</FONT>
</DD>
<DT STYLE='FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;MARGIN-BOTTOM:-9PT;'>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
	&#149;
</FONT>
</DT>
<DD STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
	Level&nbsp;2
	inputs are inputs other than quoted prices included within Level&nbsp;1 that are observable for the asset or liability, either directly
	or&nbsp;indirectly.
<BR>
<BR>
</FONT>
</DD>
<DT STYLE='FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;MARGIN-BOTTOM:-9PT;'>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
	&#149;
</FONT>
</DT>
<DD STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
	Level&nbsp;3
	inputs are unobservable inputs for the asset or liability.
</FONT>
</DD>
</DL>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
	When
	appropriate, valuations are adjusted for various factors including credit considerations. Such adjustments are generally based on available market evidence. In the
	absence of such evidence, management's best estimate is&nbsp;used.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
<B>
<!-- COMMAND=ADD_TXTHEX,"PMS287" -->
</B>
</FONT>
<FONT COLOR="#0C2E82" SIZE=1>
<B>
	(b)&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Fair Value of Financial Instruments
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
	The carrying value of cash and cash equivalents, accounts receivable and other, accounts payable and accrued liabilities, accounts payable to affiliates, accrued interest
	and short-term debt approximate their fair values because of the short maturity or duration of these instruments, or because the instruments bear a variable rate of interest or a rate that
	approximates current rates. The fair value of the Partnership's long-term debt is estimated by discounting the future cash flows of each instrument at estimated current borrowing rates. The fair
	value of interest rate derivatives is calculated using the income approach which uses period-end market rates and applies a discounted cash flow valuation model.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
	The
	estimated fair value of the Partnership's debt as at December&nbsp;31, 2015 and 2014 are as&nbsp;follows:
</FONT>
</P>
<!-- USER-SPECIFIED TAGGED TABLE -->
<EFX_UNIDENTIFIED_TABLE>

<!-- END OF USER-SPECIFIED TAGGED TABLE -->
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
	Long-term
	debt is recorded at amortized cost and classified in Level&nbsp;II of the fair value hierarchy for fair value disclosure purposes. Interest rate derivative
	assets and liabilities are classified in Level&nbsp;II for all periods presented where the fair value is determined by using valuation techniques that refer to observable market data or
	estimated market&nbsp;prices.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
	Market
	risk is the risk that changes in market interest rates may result in fluctuations in the fair values or cash flows of financial instruments. The Partnership's
	floating rate debt is subject to LIBOR benchmark interest rate risk. The Partnership uses interest rate derivatives to manage its exposure to interest rate risk. We regularly assess the impact of
	interest rate fluctuations on future cash flows and evaluate hedging opportunities to mitigate our interest rate&nbsp;risk.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
	The
	Partnership hedged interest payments on $150&nbsp;million of our $500&nbsp;million variable-rate 2013 Term Loan Facility with interest rate swaps effective
	September&nbsp;3, 2013 and maturing July&nbsp;1, 2018, at a weighted average fixed interest rate of 2.79&nbsp;percent. The interest rate swaps are structured such that the cash flows of the
	derivative instruments match those of the variable rate of interest on the 2013 Term Loan Facility. At December&nbsp;31, 2015 and 2014, the fair value of the interest rate swaps accounted for as
	cash flow hedges was a liability of $1&nbsp;million (both on a gross and net basis) (December&nbsp;31, 2013&nbsp;&#150;&nbsp;less than $1&nbsp;million). In 2015, the
	Partnership did not record any amounts in net income related to ineffectiveness for interest rate hedges. The change in fair value of interest rate derivative instruments recognized in other
	comprehensive income was nil million for the year ended December&nbsp;31,
	2015 (2014&nbsp;&#150;&nbsp;$1&nbsp;million; 2013&nbsp;&#150;&nbsp;less than $1&nbsp;million). In 2015, the net realized loss related to the
	interest rate swaps was $2&nbsp;million and was included in financial charges and other (2014&nbsp;&#150;&nbsp;$2&nbsp;million;
	2013&nbsp;&#150;&nbsp;$1&nbsp;million).
</FONT>
</P>
<P ALIGN="RIGHT" STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
<B>
<!-- COMMAND=ADD_TXTHEX,"PMS287" -->
</B>
</FONT>
<FONT COLOR="#0C2E82" SIZE=1>
<B>
	F-24
</B>
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;2015
	ANNUAL REPORT
</FONT>
</P>
<HR NOSHADE>

<!-- ZEQ.=11,SEQ=105,EFW="2227406",CP="TC PIPELINES, LP",DN="1",CHK=611033,FOLIO='F-24',FILE='DISK132:[15ZCW1.15ZCW77001]FI77001A.;44',USER='IMORTON',CD='24-FEB-2016;14:42' -->
<A NAME="A2227406Z10-K_HTM_PAGE_FI77001_1_25">
</A>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
	The
	Partnership has no master netting agreements, however, contracts contain provisions with rights of offset. The Partnership has elected to present the fair value of
	derivative instruments with the right to offset on a gross basis in the balance sheet. Had the Partnership elected to present these instruments on a net basis, there would be no effect on the
	consolidated balance sheet as of December&nbsp;31, 2015 and&nbsp;2014.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
	Counterparty
	credit risk represents the financial loss that the Partnership would experience if a counterparty to a financial instrument failed to meet its obligations
	in accordance with the terms and conditions of the financial instruments with the Partnership. Our maximum counterparty credit exposure with respect to financial instruments at the balance sheet
	date consists primarily of the carrying amount, which approximates fair value, of non-derivative financial assets, such as accounts receivable, as well as the fair value of derivative financial
	assets. We review our accounts receivable regularly and record allowances for doubtful accounts using the specific identification method. At December&nbsp;31, 2015, we had not incurred any
	significant credit losses and had no significant amounts past due or impaired. At December&nbsp;31, 2015 and 2014, the Partnership's maximum counterparty credit exposure consisted of accounts
	receivable of $35&nbsp;million.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
<B>
<!-- COMMAND=ADD_TXTHEX,"PMS287" -->
</B>
</FONT>
<FONT COLOR="#0C2E82" SIZE=1>
<B>
	(c)&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Other
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
	As discussed more fully in Note&nbsp;4, we recognized $199&nbsp;million impairment to our equity investment in Great Lakes during the fourth quarter of 2015, reflected
	as Impairment of equity-method investment on our Statement of Income for the year ended December&nbsp;31, 2015. The estimated fair value measurement of this investment is classified as
	Level&nbsp;3. In the determination of the fair value, we used an income and market approach based on internal forecasts on expected future cash flows and applied appropriate discount rates. The
	determination of expected future cash flows involved significant assumptions and estimates regarding revenue, operating and maintenance costs and future growth&nbsp;capital.
</FONT>
</P>

<B>
	NOTE 20&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;REGULATORY MATTERS
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
<I>
	North Baja&nbsp;&#150;&nbsp;
</I>
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
	On January&nbsp;6, 2014, FERC approved North Baja's application to
	temporarily abandon compression associated with the original design of its pipeline system. This temporary abandonment will preserve replacement options while reducing maintenance requirements and
	related expenses without any reduction in capacity or impact to existing firm transportation service.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
<I>
	Tuscarora&nbsp;&#150;&nbsp;
</I>
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
	On January&nbsp;21, 2016, the FERC issued an Order
	(the&nbsp;January&nbsp;21 Order) initiating an investigation pursuant to Section&nbsp;5 of the Natural Gas Act (NGA) to determine whether Tuscarora's existing rates for jurisdictional
	services are just and reasonable. Tuscarora is currently preparing its response as required by the January&nbsp;21 Order. We cannot predict the outcome or potential impact of this proceeding to
	Tuscarora at this&nbsp;time.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
<B>
<!-- COMMAND=ADD_TXTHEX,"PMS287" -->
</B>
</FONT>
<FONT COLOR="#0C2E82" SIZE=1>
<B>
	NOTE 21&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;CONTINGENCIES
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
<I>
	Employees Retirement System of the City of St.&nbsp;Louis v. TC&nbsp;PipeLines&nbsp;GP,&nbsp;Inc., et&nbsp;al
</I>
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
	. On
	October&nbsp;13, 2015, an alleged unitholder of the Partnership filed a class action and derivative complaint in the Delaware Court of Chancery against the General Partner, TransCanada American
	Investments,&nbsp;Ltd. (TAIL) and TransCanada, and the Partnership as a nominal defendant. The complaint alleges direct and derivative claims for breach of contract, breach of the duty of good
	faith and fair dealing, aiding and abetting breach of contract, and tortious interference in connection with the 2015 GTN Acquisition, including the issuance by the Partnership of
	$95&nbsp;million in Class&nbsp;B Units and amendments to the Partnership Agreement to provide for the issuance of the Class&nbsp;B Units. Plaintiff seeks, among other things, to enjoin
	future issuances of Class&nbsp;B Units to TransCanada or any of its subsidiaries, disgorgement of certain distributions to the General Partner, TransCanada and any related entities, return of
	some or all of the Class&nbsp;B Units to the Partnership, rescission of the amendments to the Partnership Agreement, monetary damages and attorney fees. The Partnership has moved to dismiss the
	complaint and intends to defend vigorously against the claims asserted.
</FONT>
</P>

</A>
<EFX_SUBSEQUENT_EVENTS>
<A NAME="FIS_SUBSEQUENT_EVENTS"></A>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
<B>
<!-- COMMAND=ADD_TXTHEX,"PMS287" -->
</B>
</FONT>
<FONT COLOR="#0C2E82" SIZE=1>
<B>
	NOTE 22&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;SUBSEQUENT EVENTS
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
	Management of the Partnership has reviewed subsequent events through February&nbsp;26, 2016, the date the financial statements were issued, and concluded there were no
	events or transactions during this period that would require recognition or disclosure in the consolidated financial statements other than what is disclosed here and/or those already disclosed in
	the preceding notes.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
	On
	January&nbsp;21, 2016, the board of directors of our General Partner declared the Partnership's fourth quarter 2015 cash distribution in the amount of $0.89 per
	common unit. The fourth quarter cash distribution, which was paid on February&nbsp;12, 2016 to unitholders of record as of February&nbsp;2, 2016, totaled $59&nbsp;million and was paid in the
	following manner: $57&nbsp;million to common unitholders (including $5&nbsp;million to the General Partner as holder of 5,797,106&nbsp;common units and $10&nbsp;million to another
	subsidiary of TransCanada as holder of 11,287,725&nbsp;common units) and $2&nbsp;million to the General Partner in respect of its effective two percent general partner interest, which included
	IDRs of $1&nbsp;million.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
	On
	January&nbsp;21, 2016, the board of directors of our General Partner declared distributions to Class&nbsp;B unitholders in the amount of $12&nbsp;million and
	was paid on February&nbsp;12, 2016. The Class&nbsp;B distribution represents an amount based upon 30&nbsp;percent of GTN's distributable cash flow during the nine months ended
	December&nbsp;31, 2015 less $15&nbsp;million.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
	Northern
	Border declared its fourth quarter 2015 distribution of $44&nbsp;million on January&nbsp;11, 2016, of which the Partnership received its 50&nbsp;percent
	share or $22&nbsp;million. The distribution was paid on February&nbsp;1,&nbsp;2016.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
	Great
	Lakes declared its fourth quarter 2015 distribution of $42&nbsp;million on January&nbsp;11, 2016, of which the Partnership received its 46.45&nbsp;percent
	share or $20&nbsp;million. The distribution was paid on February&nbsp;1,&nbsp;2016.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
	On
	January&nbsp;1, 2016, the Partnership acquired a 49.9&nbsp;percent interest in PNGTS from a subsidiary of TransCanada (PNGTS Acquisition). The total purchase
	price of the PNGTS Acquisition was $223&nbsp;million plus preliminary purchase price adjustments of $3&nbsp;million. The purchase price consisted of $191&nbsp;million in cash (including the
	preliminary purchase price adjustment of $3&nbsp;million) and the assumption of $35&nbsp;million in proportional PNGTS debt. The Partnership funded the cash portion of the transaction using
	proceeds received from our ATM program and additional borrowings under our Senior Credit Facility. The purchase agreement provides for additional payments to TransCanada ranging from
	$5&nbsp;million up to a total of $50&nbsp;million if pipeline capacity is expanded to various thresholds during the fifteen year period following the date of closing. The Partnership will
	account for this acquisition as a transaction between entities under common control (refer to Note&nbsp;2&nbsp;&#150;&nbsp;Significant accounting policies)
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
	PNGTS
	is a high-capacity, high-pressure interstate natural gas pipeline which began serving New&nbsp;England's energy needs in March, 1999. The pipeline connects with
	the TQM at the Canadian border and shares facilities with the Maritimes and Northeast Pipeline from Westbrook, Maine to a connection with the Tennessee Gas Pipeline System near Boston,
	Massachusetts.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
	On
	January&nbsp;25, 2016, the Partnership hedged interest payments on the remaining $350&nbsp;million of the $500&nbsp;million variable-rate 2013 Term Loan
	Facility with interest rate swaps from January&nbsp;27, 2016 through July&nbsp;1, 2018, where the weighted average fixed rate paid is 2.10&nbsp;percent. The interest rate swaps are
	structured such that the cash flows of the derivative instruments match those of the variable rate of interest on the 2013 Term Loan&nbsp;Facility.
</FONT>
</P>
<P ALIGN="RIGHT" STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">

</FONT>

	ANNUAL REPORT

</P>

<BR>
	INDEPENDENT AUDITORS' REPORT
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<B>
	The Management Committee
<BR>
	Northern Border Pipeline Company:
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<B>
<!-- COMMAND=ADD_TXTHEX,"PMS287" -->
</B>
</FONT>
<FONT COLOR="#0C2E82" SIZE=2>
<B>
	Report on the Financial Statements
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	We have audited the accompanying financial statements of Northern Border Pipeline Company (the&nbsp;Company), which comprise the balance sheets as of December&nbsp;31, 2015
	and 2014, and the related statements of income, comprehensive income, changes in partners' equity, and cash flows for each of the years in the three-year period ended December&nbsp;31, 2015, and the
	related notes to the financial statements.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<I>
	Management's Responsibility for the Financial Statements
</I>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	Management is responsible for the preparation and fair presentation of these financial statements in accordance with U.S.&nbsp;generally accepted accounting principles; this
	includes the design, implementation, and maintenance of internal control relevant to the preparation and fair presentation of financial statements that are free from material misstatement, whether due
	to fraud or&nbsp;error.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<I>
	Auditors' Responsibility
</I>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	Our responsibility is to express an opinion on these financial statements based on our audits. We conducted our audits in accordance with auditing standards generally accepted
	in the United&nbsp;States of America. Those standards require that we plan and perform the audit to obtain reasonable assurance about whether the financial statements are free from material
	misstatement.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	An
	audit involves performing procedures to obtain audit evidence about the amounts and disclosures in the financial statements. The procedures selected depend on the
	auditors' judgment, including the assessment of the risks of material misstatement of the financial statements, whether due to fraud or error. In making those risk assessments, the auditor considers
	internal control relevant to the entity's preparation and fair presentation of the financial statements in order to design audit procedures that are appropriate in the circumstances, but not for the
	purpose of expressing an opinion on the effectiveness of the entity's internal control. Accordingly, we express no such opinion. An audit also includes evaluating the appropriateness of accounting
	policies used and the reasonableness of significant accounting estimates made by management, as well as evaluating the overall presentation of the financial statements.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	We
	believe that the audit evidence we have obtained is sufficient and appropriate to provide a basis for our audit&nbsp;opinion.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<I>
	Opinion
</I>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	In our opinion, the financial statements referred to above present fairly, in all material respects, the financial position of Northern Border Pipeline Company as of
	December&nbsp;31, 2015 and 2014, and the results of its operations and its cash flows for each of the years in the three-year period ended December&nbsp;31, 2015, in accordance with
	U.S.&nbsp;generally accepted accounting principles.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	/s/
	KPMG&nbsp;LLP
<BR>
</FONT>
</P>

<B>

<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
<B>
<!-- COMMAND=ADD_TXTHEX,"PMS287" -->
</B>
</FONT>
<FONT COLOR="#0C2E82" SIZE=1>
<B>
	1.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;DESCRIPTION OF BUSINESS
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
	Northern Border Pipeline Company (the&nbsp;Partnership) is a Texas general partnership formed in 1978. The Partnership owns a 1,260-mile natural gas transmission pipeline
	system, which includes an additional 149&nbsp;pipeline miles parallel to the original system, extending from the United&nbsp;States-Canadian border near Port of Morgan, Montana, to a terminus near
	North Hayden, Indiana. The partners and ownership percentages at December&nbsp;31, 2015 and 2014 were as&nbsp;follows:
</FONT>
</P>

<TABLE WIDTH="100%" BORDER=0 CELLSPACING=0 CELLPADDING=0>

<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
	The
	Partnership is managed by a Management Committee that consists of four members. Each partner designates two members and TC&nbsp;PipeLines designates one of its members
	as&nbsp;chairman.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
<B>
<!-- COMMAND=ADD_TXTHEX,"PMS287" -->
</B>
</FONT>
<FONT COLOR="#0C2E82" SIZE=1>
<B>
	2.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;SUMMARY OF SIGNIFICANT ACCOUNTING POLICIES
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
<B>
<!-- COMMAND=ADD_TXTHEX,"PMS287" -->
</B>
</FONT>
<FONT COLOR="#0C2E82" SIZE=1>
<B>
	(a)&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Use of Estimates
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
	The preparation of the financial statements in accordance with U.S.&nbsp;generally accepted accounting principles (GAAP) requires management to make estimates and assumptions
	that affect the reported amounts of assets, liabilities, revenues and expenses as well as the disclosure of contingent assets and liabilities during the reported period. Although management believes
	these estimates are reasonable, actual results could differ from these estimates in the financial statements and accompanying notes.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
<B>
<!-- COMMAND=ADD_TXTHEX,"PMS287" -->
</B>
</FONT>
<FONT COLOR="#0C2E82" SIZE=1>
<B>
	(b)&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Cash and Cash Equivalents
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
	The Partnership's cash and cash equivalents consist of cash and highly liquid short-term investments with original maturities of three months or less and are recorded at cost,
	which approximates fair&nbsp;value.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
<B>
<!-- COMMAND=ADD_TXTHEX,"PMS287" -->
</B>
</FONT>
<FONT COLOR="#0C2E82" SIZE=1>
<B>
	(c)&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Trade Accounts Receivable
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
	Trade accounts receivable are recorded at the invoiced amount and do not bear interest, except for those receivables subject to late charges. The Partnership maintains an
	allowance for doubtful accounts for estimated losses on accounts receivable, if it is determined the Partnership will not collect all or part of the outstanding receivable balance. The Partnership
	regularly reviews its allowance for doubtful accounts and establishes or adjusts the allowance as necessary using the specific-identification method. Account balances are charged to the allowance
	after all means of collection have been exhausted and the potential for recovery is no longer considered probable. Accounts written off in 2015 and 2014 were not material to the Partnership's
	financial statements.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
<B>
<!-- COMMAND=ADD_TXTHEX,"PMS287" -->
</B>
</FONT>
<FONT COLOR="#0C2E82" SIZE=1>
<B>
	(d)&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Natural Gas Imbalances
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
	Natural gas imbalances occur when the actual amount of natural gas delivered to or received from a pipeline system differs from the amount of natural gas scheduled to be
	delivered or received. The Partnership values these imbalances due to or from shippers and interconnecting parties at current index prices. Imbalances are settled in-kind, subject to the terms of the
	Partnership's tariff.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
	Imbalances
	due from others are reported on the balance sheets as trade accounts receivable and related party receivables. Imbalances owed to others are reported on the
	balance sheets as trade accounts payable and accounts payable to affiliates. In addition, the Partnership classifies all imbalances as current as the Partnership expects to settle them within
	a&nbsp;year.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
<B>
<!-- COMMAND=ADD_TXTHEX,"PMS287" -->
</B>
</FONT>
<FONT COLOR="#0C2E82" SIZE=1>
<B>
	(e)&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Material and Supplies
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
	The Partnership's inventory consists of materials and supplies. The materials and supplies are valued at cost with cost determined using the average cost&nbsp;method.
</FONT>
</P>
<P ALIGN="RIGHT" STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
<B>
<!-- COMMAND=ADD_TXTHEX,"PMS287" -->
</B>
</FONT>
<FONT COLOR="#0C2E82" SIZE=1>
<B>
	F-32
</B>
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;2015
	ANNUAL REPORT
</FONT>
</P>
<HR NOSHADE>
<P STYLE='FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE:ALWAYS'>
</P>
<!-- ZEQ.=1,SEQ=113,EFW="2227406",CP="TC PIPELINES, LP",DN="1",CHK=839038,FOLIO='F-32',FILE='DISK132:[15ZCW1.15ZCW77001]FO77001A.;9',USER='PANDERS',CD='22-FEB-2016;22:41' -->
<A NAME="A2227406Z10-K_HTM_PAGE_FO77001_1_33">
</A>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
<B>
<!-- COMMAND=ADD_TXTHEX,"PMS287" -->
</B>
</FONT>
<FONT COLOR="#0C2E82" SIZE=1>
<B>
	(f)&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Accounting for Regulated Operations
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
	The Partnership's natural gas pipeline is subject to the jurisdiction of the Federal Energy Regulatory Commission (FERC) under the Natural Gas Act of 1938 and the Natural Gas
	Policy Act of 1978. Financial Accounting Standards Board Accounting Standards Codification (ASC) 980,
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
<I>
	Regulated Operations
</I>
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
	, provides that rate regulated
	enterprises account for and report assets and liabilities consistent with the economic effect of the way in which regulators establish rates, if the rates are designed to recover the costs of
	providing the regulated service and if the
	competitive environment makes it probable that such rates can be charged and collected. The Partnership evaluates the continued applicability of regulatory accounting, considering such factors as
	regulatory charges, the impact of competition, and the ability to recover regulatory assets as set forth in ASC 980. Accordingly, certain assets and liabilities that result from the regulated
	ratemaking process are reflected on the balance sheets as regulatory assets and regulatory liabilities.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
	The
	following table presents regulatory assets and liabilities at December&nbsp;31, 2015 and&nbsp;2014:
</FONT>
</P>

<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
	Volumetric
	fuel tracker assets or liabilities are settled with in-kind exchanges with customers continually
<BR>
<BR>
</FONT>
</DD>
<DT STYLE='FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;MARGIN-BOTTOM:-9PT;'>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:6PT;POSITION:RELATIVE;TOP:-2PT;ADD_SUP:2PT;">
	(b)
</FONT>
</FONT>
</DT>
<DD STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
	South
	Dakota use tax assessment surrounding legal proceedings (refer to Note&nbsp;4(a))
<BR>
<BR>
</FONT>
</DD>
<DT STYLE='FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;MARGIN-BOTTOM:-9PT;'>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:6PT;POSITION:RELATIVE;TOP:-2PT;ADD_SUP:2PT;">
	(c)
</FONT>
</FONT>
</DT>
<DD STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
	Compressor
	usage surcharge is designed to track the recovery of the actual costs related to both electricity usage at the Partnership's electric
	compressors and compressor fuel use taxes imposed on the consumption of natural gas powered stations along the Partnership's pipeline system (refer to Note&nbsp;4(b))
<BR>
<BR>
</FONT>
</DD>
<DT STYLE='FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;MARGIN-BOTTOM:-9PT;'>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:6PT;POSITION:RELATIVE;TOP:-2PT;ADD_SUP:2PT;">
	(d)
</FONT>
</FONT>
</DT>
<DD STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
	Negative
	salvage accrued for estimated net costs of removal of transmission plant has a settlement period related to the estimated life of the assets
	(refer to Note&nbsp;2(g))
</FONT>
</DD>
</DL>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
<B>
<!-- COMMAND=ADD_TXTHEX,"PMS287" -->
</B>
</FONT>
<FONT COLOR="#0C2E82" SIZE=1>
<B>
	(g)&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Property, Plant and Equipment
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
	Property, plant and equipment are recorded at their original cost of construction. For assets the Partnership constructs, direct costs, such as labor and materials, and indirect
	costs, such as overhead, interest, and an equity return component on regulated businesses as allowed by the FERC, are capitalized. The Partnership capitalizes major units of property replacements or
	improvements and expenses minor&nbsp;items.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
	The
	Partnership uses the composite (group) method to depreciate property, plant and equipment. Under this method, assets with similar lives and characteristics are grouped
	and depreciated as one asset. The depreciation rate is applied to the total cost of the group until its net book value equals its salvage value. All asset groups are depreciated using depreciation
	rates approved in the Partnership's last rate proceeding. Currently, the Partnership's depreciation rates vary from 2.02% to 20% per year. Using these rates, the remaining depreciable life of these
	assets ranges from 2 to 39&nbsp;years.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
<B>
<!-- COMMAND=ADD_TXTHEX,"PMS287" -->
</B>
</FONT>
<FONT COLOR="#0C2E82" SIZE=1>
<B>
	F-33
</B>
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;TC
	PIPELINES, LP
</FONT>
</P>
<HR NOSHADE>
<P STYLE='FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE:ALWAYS'>
</P>
<!-- ZEQ.=2,SEQ=114,EFW="2227406",CP="TC PIPELINES, LP",DN="1",CHK=770483,FOLIO='F-33',FILE='DISK132:[15ZCW1.15ZCW77001]FO77001A.;9',USER='PANDERS',CD='22-FEB-2016;22:41' -->
<A NAME="A2227406Z10-K_HTM_PAGE_FO77001_1_34">
</A>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
	When
	property, plant and equipment are retired, the Partnership charges accumulated depreciation and amortization for the original cost of the assets in addition to the cost
	to remove, sell, or dispose of the assets, less their salvage value. The Partnership does not recognize a gain or loss unless an entire operating unit is sold or retired. The Partnership includes
	gains or losses on dispositions of operating units in&nbsp;income.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
	The
	Partnership capitalizes a carrying cost on funds invested in the construction of long-lived assets. This carrying cost includes a return on the investment financed by
	debt and equity allowance for funds used during construction (AFUDC). AFUDC is calculated based on the Partnership's average cost of debt and equity. Capitalized carrying costs for AFUDC debt and
	equity are reflected as an increase in the cost of the asset on the balance&nbsp;sheets.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
<B>
<!-- COMMAND=ADD_TXTHEX,"PMS287" -->
</B>
</FONT>
<FONT COLOR="#0C2E82" SIZE=1>
<B>
	(h)&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Long-Lived Assets
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
	Long-lived assets, such as property, plant and equipment, and purchased intangible assets subject to amortization, are reviewed for impairment whenever events or changes in
	circumstances indicate that the carrying amount of an asset may not be recoverable. If circumstances require a long-lived asset or asset group be tested for possible impairment, the Partnership first
	compares undiscounted cash flows expected to be generated by that asset or asset group to its carrying value. If the carrying value of the long-lived asset or asset group is not recoverable on an
	undiscounted cash flow basis, an impairment is recognized to the extent that the carrying value exceeds its fair value. Fair value is determined through various valuation techniques including
	discounted cash flow models, quoted market values, and third-party independent appraisals, as considered necessary.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
<B>
<!-- COMMAND=ADD_TXTHEX,"PMS287" -->
</B>
</FONT>
<FONT COLOR="#0C2E82" SIZE=1>
<B>
	(i)&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Revenue Recognition
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
	The Partnership's revenues are primarily generated from transportation services. Revenues for all services are based on the quantity of gas delivered or subscribed at a price
	specified in the contract. For the Partnership's transportation services, reservation revenues are recognized on firm contracted capacity ratably over the contract period regardless of the amount of
	natural gas that is transported. For the Partnership's interruptible or volumetric-based services, the Partnership records revenues when physical deliveries of natural gas are made at the agreed-upon
	delivery point. The Partnership does not take ownership of the gas that it transports. The Partnership is subject to FERC regulations, and as a result, revenues the Partnership collects may be subject
	to refund in a rate proceeding. The Partnership establishes provision for these potential refunds. As of December&nbsp;31, 2015 and 2014, there are no provisions reflected in these financial
	statements.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
<B>
<!-- COMMAND=ADD_TXTHEX,"PMS287" -->
</B>
</FONT>
<FONT COLOR="#0C2E82" SIZE=1>
<B>
	(j)&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Asset Retirement Obligations
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
	The Partnership accounts for asset retirement obligations pursuant to the provisions of ASC 410-20,
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
<I>
	Asset Retirement Obligations
</I>
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
	.
	ASC 410-20&nbsp;requires the Partnership to record the fair value of an asset retirement obligation as a liability in the period in which it incurs a legal obligation associated with the retirement
	of tangible long lived assets that result from the acquisition, construction, development, and/or normal use of the assets. ASC 410-20&nbsp;also requires the Partnership to record a corresponding
	asset that is depreciated over the life of the asset. Subsequent to the initial measurement of the asset retirement obligation, the obligation is to be adjusted at the end of each period to reflect
	the passage of time and changes in the estimated future cash flows underlying the&nbsp;obligation.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
	The
	fair value of a liability for an asset retirement obligation is recorded during the period in which the liability is incurred, if a reasonable estimate of fair value can
	be made. The Partnership has determined that asset retirement obligations exist for certain of its transmission assets; however, the fair value of the obligations cannot be determined because the end
	of the transmission system life is not determinable with the degree of accuracy necessary to currently establish a liability for the obligations.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
	The
	Partnership has determined it has legal obligations associated with its natural gas pipelines and related transmission facilities. The obligations relate primarily to
	purging and sealing the pipelines if they are abandoned. The Partnership is also required to operate and maintain its natural gas pipeline system, and intends to do so as long as supply and demand for
	natural gas exists, which the Partnership expects for the foreseeable future. Therefore, the Partnership believes its natural gas pipeline system assets have indeterminate lives and, accordingly, has
	recorded no asset retirement obligation as of December&nbsp;31, 2015 and 2014. The Partnership continues to evaluate its asset retirement obligations and future developments that could impact
	amounts it&nbsp;records.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
<B>
<!-- COMMAND=ADD_TXTHEX,"PMS287" -->
</B>
</FONT>
<FONT COLOR="#0C2E82" SIZE=1>
<B>
	(k)&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Derivative Instruments and Hedging Activities
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
	The Partnership recognizes all derivative instruments as either assets or liabilities in the balance sheet at their respective fair values. For derivatives designated in hedging
	relationships, changes in the fair value are either offset through earnings against the change in fair value of the hedged item attributable to the risk being hedged or recognized in accumulated other
	comprehensive income, to the extent the derivative is effective at offsetting the changes in cash flows being hedged until the hedged item affects earnings.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
	The
	Partnership only enters into derivative contracts that it intends to designate as a hedge of a forecasted transaction or the variability of cash flows to be received or
	paid related to a recognized asset or liability (cash flow hedge). For all hedging relationships, the Partnership formally documents the hedging relationship and its risk-management objective and
	strategy for undertaking the hedge, the hedging instrument, the hedged transaction, the nature of the risk being hedged, how the hedging instrument's effectiveness in offsetting the hedged
</FONT>
</P>
<P ALIGN="RIGHT" STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
<B>
<!-- COMMAND=ADD_TXTHEX,"PMS287" -->
</B>
</FONT>
<FONT COLOR="#0C2E82" SIZE=1>
<B>
	F-34
</B>
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;2015
	ANNUAL REPORT
</FONT>
</P>
<HR NOSHADE>
<P STYLE='FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE:ALWAYS'>
</P>
<!-- ZEQ.=3,SEQ=115,EFW="2227406",CP="TC PIPELINES, LP",DN="1",CHK=134773,FOLIO='F-34',FILE='DISK132:[15ZCW1.15ZCW77001]FO77001A.;9',USER='PANDERS',CD='22-FEB-2016;22:41' -->
<A NAME="A2227406Z10-K_HTM_PAGE_FO77001_1_35">
</A>
<BR>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
	risk
	will be assessed prospectively and retrospectively, and a description of the method used to measure ineffectiveness. The Partnership also formally assesses, both at the inception of the hedging
	relationship and on an ongoing basis, whether the derivatives that are used in the hedging relationships are highly effective in offsetting changes in cash flows of hedged transactions. For derivative
	instruments that are designated and qualify as part of a cash flow hedging relationship, the effective portion of the gain or loss on the derivatives is reported as a component of other comprehensive
	income and reclassified into earnings in the same period or periods during which the hedged transaction affects earnings. Gains and losses on the derivative representing either hedge ineffectiveness
	or hedge components excluded from the assessment of effectiveness are recognized in current earnings.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
	The
	Partnership discontinues hedge accounting prospectively when it determines that the derivative is no longer effective in offsetting cash flows attributable to the hedged
	risk, the derivative expires or is sold, terminated, or exercised, the cash flow hedge is de-designated because a forecasted transaction is not probable of occurring, or management determines to
	remove the designation of the cash flow&nbsp;hedge.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
	In
	all situations in which hedge accounting is discontinued and the derivative remains outstanding, the Partnership continues to carry the derivative at its fair value on
	the balance sheet and recognizes any subsequent changes in its fair value in earnings. When it is probable that a forecasted transaction will not occur, the Partnership discontinues hedge accounting
	and recognizes immediately in earnings gains and losses that were accumulated in other comprehensive income related to the hedging relationship.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
<B>
<!-- COMMAND=ADD_TXTHEX,"PMS287" -->
</B>
</FONT>
<FONT COLOR="#0C2E82" SIZE=1>
<B>
	(l)&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Debt Issuance Costs
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
	Costs related to the issuance of debt are deferred and amortized using the effective-interest rate method over the term of the related&nbsp;debt.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
	The
	Partnership amortizes premiums, discounts, and expenses incurred in connection with the issuance of debt consistent with the terms of the respective debt instrument.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
<B>
<!-- COMMAND=ADD_TXTHEX,"PMS287" -->
</B>
</FONT>
<FONT COLOR="#0C2E82" SIZE=1>
<B>
	(m)&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Operating Leases
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
	The Partnership has non-cancelable operating leases for office space and rights-of-way. The Partnership records rent expense straight-line over the life of the&nbsp;lease.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
<B>
<!-- COMMAND=ADD_TXTHEX,"PMS287" -->
</B>
</FONT>
<FONT COLOR="#0C2E82" SIZE=1>
<B>
	(n)&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Contingencies
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
	The Partnership recognizes liabilities for contingencies when it has an exposure that, when fully analyzed, indicates it is both probable that a liability has been incurred and
	the amount of loss can be reasonably estimated. Where the most likely outcome of a contingency can be reasonably estimated, the Partnership accrues a liability for that amount. Where the most likely
	outcome cannot be estimated, a range of potential losses is established and if no one amount in that range is more likely than any other, the lower end of the range is&nbsp;accrued.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
<B>
<!-- COMMAND=ADD_TXTHEX,"PMS287" -->
</B>
</FONT>
<FONT COLOR="#0C2E82" SIZE=1>
<B>
	(o)&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Income Taxes
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
	Income taxes are the responsibility of the partners and are not reflected in these financial statements.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
<B>
<!-- COMMAND=ADD_TXTHEX,"PMS287" -->
</B>
</FONT>
<FONT COLOR="#0C2E82" SIZE=1>
<B>
	(p)&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Fair Value
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
	For cash and cash equivalents, receivables, accounts payable and certain accrued expenses, the carrying amount approximates fair value due to the short maturities of these
	instruments. For long-term debt instruments, fair value is estimated based upon market values (if&nbsp;applicable) or on the current interest rates available to us for debt with similar terms and
	remaining maturities. Considerable judgment is required in developing these estimates.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
<B>
<!-- COMMAND=ADD_TXTHEX,"PMS287" -->
</B>
</FONT>
<FONT COLOR="#0C2E82" SIZE=1>
<B>
	3.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;FUTURE ACCOUNTING CHANGES
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
<B>
<!-- COMMAND=ADD_TXTHEX,"PMS287" -->
</B>
</FONT>
<FONT COLOR="#0C2E82" SIZE=1>
<B>
	Revenue from contracts with customers
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
	In May&nbsp;2014, the Financial Accounting Standards Board (FASB) issued Accounting Standards Update (ASU) No.&nbsp;2014-09 "Revenue from Contracts with Customers (Topic
	606)." This guidance supersedes the revenue recognition requirements in Topic 605, Revenue Recognition and most industry-specific guidance. This new guidance requires that an entity recognizes revenue
	to depict the transfer of promised goods or services to customers in an amount that reflects the consideration to which the company expects to be entitled in exchange for those goods or services. On
	July&nbsp;9, 2015, the FASB voted to defer the effective date by one year to December&nbsp;15, 2017 for annual reporting periods beginning after that date. The FASB also voted to permit early
	adoption of the standard, but not before the original effective date of December&nbsp;15, 2016. This new guidance, once effective, allows two methods in which the amendment can be applied:
	(1)&nbsp;retrospectively to each prior reporting period presented, or (2)&nbsp;retrospectively with the cumulative effect recognized at the date of initial application. The Partnership is
	currently evaluating the impact of the adoption of this ASU and has not yet determined the effect on its financial statements.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
<B>
<!-- COMMAND=ADD_TXTHEX,"PMS287" -->
</B>
</FONT>
<FONT COLOR="#0C2E82" SIZE=1>
<B>
	F-35
</B>
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;TC
	PIPELINES, LP
</FONT>
</P>
<HR NOSHADE>
<P STYLE='FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE:ALWAYS'>
</P>
<!-- ZEQ.=4,SEQ=116,EFW="2227406",CP="TC PIPELINES, LP",DN="1",CHK=1007998,FOLIO='F-35',FILE='DISK132:[15ZCW1.15ZCW77001]FO77001A.;9',USER='PANDERS',CD='22-FEB-2016;22:41' -->
<A NAME="A2227406Z10-K_HTM_PAGE_FO77001_1_36">
</A>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
<B>
<!-- COMMAND=ADD_TXTHEX,"PMS287" -->
</B>
</FONT>
<FONT COLOR="#0C2E82" SIZE=1>
<B>
	Imputation of interest
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
	In April&nbsp;2015, the FASB issued ASU No.&nbsp;2015-03 "Interest&nbsp;&#150;&nbsp;Imputation of Interest (Subtopic 835-30)," an amendment of
	previously issued guidance on imputation of interest. This updated guidance requires debt issuance costs be presented in the balance sheet as a direct deduction from the carrying amount of debt
	liabilities, consistent with debt discount or premiums. The recognition and measurement for debt issuance costs would not be affected. This guidance is effective from January&nbsp;1, 2016 and early
	application is permitted. This guidance should be adopted on a retrospective basis, wherein the balance sheet of each individual period presented would be adjusted to reflect the period-specific
	effects of applying the new guidance. The application of this amendment will result in a reclassification of debt issuance costs currently recorded in Other assets to an offset of their respective
	debt liabilities.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
<B>
<!-- COMMAND=ADD_TXTHEX,"PMS287" -->
</B>
</FONT>
<FONT COLOR="#0C2E82" SIZE=1>
<B>
	4.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;COMMITMENTS AND CONTINGENCIES
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
<B>
<!-- COMMAND=ADD_TXTHEX,"PMS287" -->
</B>
</FONT>
<FONT COLOR="#0C2E82" SIZE=1>
<B>
	(a)&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Legal Proceedings
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
<I>
	State of South Dakota Use Tax Appeal
</I>
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
	&nbsp;&#150;&nbsp;On February&nbsp;28, 2011, the State of South Dakota
	assessed a use tax in the amount of approximately $6&nbsp;million on Northern Border for shipper supplied natural gas used to fuel compressors on Northern Border's pipeline system from
	July&nbsp;1, 2007 to December&nbsp;31, 2010. In November&nbsp;2011, Northern Border filed a Request for Hearing with the South Dakota Department of Revenue to protest the assessment. A hearing
	was held on the matter in May&nbsp;2012 and in the third quarter of 2013, the South Dakota Department of Revenue determined that the gas used by Northern Border to fuel compressors is taxable. In
	October&nbsp;2013, Northern Border filed an appeal of this decision in the South Dakota Circuit Court, Sixth Judicial Circuit (Circuit Court). In May&nbsp;2014, the Circuit Court issued a
	Memorandum Decision reversing the Final Decision of the South Dakota Department of Revenue. The Circuit Court found that the
	compression of natural gas and the natural gas burned in that process is a function of natural gas transportation and therefore exempt from use tax. The South Dakota Department of Revenue filed an
	appeal to the Circuit Court decision on July&nbsp;23, 2014. Briefs were submitted to the South Dakota Supreme Court and oral argument was held on March&nbsp;24, 2015. On August&nbsp;5, 2015, the
	South Dakota Supreme Court issued its decision in Northern Border Pipeline v. South Dakota Department of Revenue, ruling that the South Dakota Department of Revenue could not assess use tax on gas
	burned in compressors on Northern Border's pipeline located in South Dakota because Northern Border did not own the gas. The opinion affirmed the Circuit Court's reversal of the use tax assessment by
	the Department of Revenue and resulted in the reversal of the $15.5&nbsp;million recorded liability and the related deferred asset with no impact to the Partnership's earnings.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
<B>
<!-- COMMAND=ADD_TXTHEX,"PMS287" -->
</B>
</FONT>
<FONT COLOR="#0C2E82" SIZE=1>
<B>
	(b)&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Regulatory Matters
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
	The FERC regulates the rates and charges for transportation of natural gas in interstate commerce. Natural gas companies may not charge rates that have been determined to be
	unjust and unreasonable by the FERC. Generally, rates for interstate pipelines are based on the cost of service, including recovery of and a return on the pipeline's actual prudent historical cost
	investment. The rates and terms and conditions for service are found in each pipeline's FERC-approved tariff. Under its tariff, an interstate pipeline is allowed to charge for its services on the
	basis of stated transportation rates. Transportation rates are established periodically in FERC proceedings known as rate cases. The tariff also allows the interstate pipeline to provide services
	under negotiated and discounted rates.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
	Effective
	January&nbsp;1, 2013, the Partnership implemented new rates as a result of its Stipulation and Agreement of Settlement. The settlement includes a three-year
	moratorium on rate changes and requires the Partnership to file for new rates no later than January&nbsp;1, 2018. The settlement establishes maximum long-term transportation rates on the
	Partnership's system and current transportation rates will be reduced by approximately 11&nbsp;percent. In addition, the composite depreciation rate was reduced to 2.19&nbsp;percent from
	2.40&nbsp;percent, which prospectively increases the depreciable life of the Partnership's assets.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
	The
	compressor usage surcharge is designated to recover the actual costs of electricity at the Partnership's electric compressors and any compressor fuel use taxes imposed
	on its pipeline system. Any difference between the compressor usage surcharge collected and the actual costs for electricity and compressor fuel use taxes is recorded as either an increase to expense
	for an over recovery of actual costs or as a decrease to expense for an under recovery of actual costs, and is included in operations and maintenance expense on the income statement and as either an
	other current liability or a current asset classified as prepaid expense and other, respectively, on the balance sheets. The compressor usage surcharge rate is adjusted annually. The current liability
	or current asset will reflect the net over or under recovery of actual compressor usage related costs at the date of the balance sheet. As of December&nbsp;31, 2015 and 2014, the Partnership had
	recorded $0.1&nbsp;million as prepaid expenses and other and $1.1&nbsp;million as other current liabilities, respectively, on the accompanying balance sheets for the net under and over recoveries
	of compressor usage related&nbsp;costs.
</FONT>
</P>
<P ALIGN="RIGHT" STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
<B>
<!-- COMMAND=ADD_TXTHEX,"PMS287" -->
</B>
</FONT>
<FONT COLOR="#0C2E82" SIZE=1>
<B>
	F-36
</B>
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;2015
	ANNUAL REPORT
</FONT>
</P>

<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:ARIAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:9PT;">
	In
	August&nbsp;2004, the Partnership signed an Option Agreement and Expanded Facilities Lease (Option Agreement) with the Assiniboine and Sioux Tribes of the Fort Peck
	Indian Reservation. The Option Agreement granted to the Partnership, among other things: (i)&nbsp;an option to renew the pipeline right-of-way lease upon agreed terms and conditions on or before
	April&nbsp;1, 2011, for a term of 25&nbsp;years with a renewal right for an additional 25&nbsp;years; (ii)&nbsp;a right to use additional tribal lands for expanded facilities; and
	(iii)&nbsp;release and satisfaction of all tribal taxes against the Partnership. In consideration of this option and other benefits, the Partnership paid a lump sum amount of $7.4&nbsp;million and
	made additional annual option payments through March&nbsp;31,&nbsp;2011.
</FONT>
</P>
